e Double-Wide: Acoustic Live | publisher=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=January 3, 2016 | author=Loftus, Johnny}}</ref>\n* [[Eddie Vedder]] made a live cover version in 2008, referencing it as \"borrowed from Chicago\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reddit.com/r/pearljam/comments/5v9x3r/pearl_jam_covering_jonny_cash_hurt/?sort=new | title=Pearl Jam covering Jonny Cash - Hurt (m.youtube.com)| publisher= | accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MPyvNUwhQoI</ref>\n* [[Leona Lewis]] covered the song on her 2011 EP, ''[[Hurt: The EP]]''.\n* The cello duo [[2Cellos]] released a rendition of the song on its [[2Cellos (album)|self-titled 2011 album]], based on Johnny Cash's version.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/2cellos-mw0002157361 | title=2Cellos - 2Cellos | publisher=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=January 3, 2016 | author=O'Brien, Jon}}</ref>\n* 2012 [[Lucinda Williams]] covered the Cash version of the song in the concert and accompanying live album [[We Walk the Line]].\n*[[Eric Whitacre]] wrote a choral version of the song, composed in 2013-14 and released as a single in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ericwhitacre.com/blog/hurt|title=Hurt|date=2013-12-02|work=Eric Whitacre|access-date=2018-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Eric Whitacre and Eric Whitacre Singers|title=Hurt|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hurt/dp/B076ZV9SFP|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref>\n* 2019 [[Mumford & Sons]] performed a cover version as a ballad in their show at Quicken Loans Arena in Cleveland, Ohio, Trent Reznor's origin city.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.musikexpress.de/video-mumford-sons-covern-nine-inch-nails-hurt-1209477/ |title=Video: Mumford & Sons covern Nine Inch Nails \u201eHurt\u201c  |date= 2019-03-11  |access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n* 2019 [[The Hospital for Sick Children, Toronto|SickKids]] used a version of the song but it was sung by children. This video was released for this campaign on Oct 10 2019. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/8p6qkHvHQB0|title=Video: Sickkids VS: This Is Why [Special Edit] |date= 2019-10-10|}} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n| url = https://archive.org/details/lillustrecompig00frgoog\n| title = Johnny Cash and the Paradox of American Identity\n| last = Edwards\n| first = Leigh H.\n| publisher = [[Indiana University Press]]\n| isbn=0253220610\n| year=2009\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news\n |url=http://kdka.com/topstories/Virginia.Tech.convocation.2.282556.html \n |title=Digital Tributes Honor Virginia Tech Victims \n |work=[[KDKA-TV]] \n |date=April 18, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071222132159/http://kdka.com/topstories/Virginia.Tech.convocation.2.282556.html \n |archivedate=December 22, 2007 \n |df=mdy \n}}\n* {{cite news\n| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7378167/in_other_words_trent_reznor\n| title = In Other Words: Trent Reznor\n| author = [[Anthony DeCurtis]]\n| work = [[Rolling Stone]]\n| date = June 7, 2005\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|dhh21crSohs|NiN 1995 live concert video}}\n* {{YouTube|8AHCfZTRGiI|Johnny Cash - Hurt 2003 official music video}}\n* {{Discogs release|id=232407|name=Hurt}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|nine-inch-nails|hurt}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Nine Inch Nails}}\n{{Johnny Cash|song}}\n{{Leona Lewis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hurt (Nine Inch Nails Song)}}\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:1994 songs]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:American Recordings (record label) singles]]\n[[Category:Gothic rock songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video]]\n[[Category:Johnny Cash songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Mark Romanek]]\n[[Category:Nine Inch Nails songs]]\n[[Category:Self-harm in fiction]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Flood (producer)]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rick Rubin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Songs about heroin]]\n[[Category:Songs about suicide]]\n[[Category:Songs about depression]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Rock ballads]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nine Inch Nails song}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name     = Hurt\n| cover    = Nine Inch Nails - Hurt Halo Ten CD cover.jpeg\n| alt      =\n| type     = promo\n| artist   = [[Nine Inch Nails]]\n| album    = [[The Downward Spiral]]\n| released = {{Start date|1995|4|17}}\n| format   = [[CD single|CD]]\n| recorded =\n| studio   = {{hlist|[[Jim Henson Company Lot|A&M Studios]], [[Record Plant Studios]] ([[Hollywood]])|[[10050 Cielo Drive|Le Pig]] ([[Benedict Canyon, Los Angeles]])}}\n| venue    =\n| genre    = {{hlist|[[Industrial rock]]<ref name=\"paradox\">{{Harvnb|Edwards|2009|pp=59\u201360}}</ref>|\n}}\n| length   = {{duration|m=6|s=12}}\n| label    = {{hlist|[[Nothing Records|Nothing]]|[[TVT Records|TVT]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]}}\n| writer   = [[Trent Reznor]]\n| producer = Trent Reznor\n|prev_title=[[Piggy (song)|Piggy]]|prev_year=1994|next_title=[[The Perfect Drug]]|next_year=1997| misc     = {{Audio sample\n | type        = song\n | file        = Hurt.ogg\n | description = \"Hurt\"\n}}\n}}\n\"'''Hurt'''\" is a song by American [[industrial rock]] band [[Nine Inch Nails]] from their second studio album, ''[[The Downward Spiral]]'' (1994), written by [[Trent Reznor]]. It was released on April 17, 1995 as a [[promotional single]] from the album.  The song received a [[Grammy Award]] nomination for [[Grammy Award for Best Rock Song|Best Rock Song]] in 1996.\n\nIn 2002, [[Johnny Cash]] covered \"Hurt\" to commercial and critical acclaim; it was one of Cash's final hits released before his death, and the related music video is considered one of the greatest of all time by publications such as ''[[NME]]''. Reznor praised Cash's interpretation of the song for its \"sincerity and meaning\", going as far as to say \"that song isn't mine anymore.\"<ref>{{cite magazine |first= Geoff |last=Rickly |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20171015203101/http://www.theninhotline.net/archives/articles/manager/display_article.php?id=11 |title=Geoff Rickly Interviews Trent Reznor |magazine=[[Alternative Press (magazine) |Alternative Press]] |location= Cleveland, [[Ohio | OH]] |date=June 26, 2004 |accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Meaning==\nThe song includes references to [[self-harm]] and [[Drug abuse|heroin addiction]], although the overall meaning of the song is disputed. Some listeners contend that the song acts as a [[suicide note]] written by the song's [[protagonist]], as a result of his [[clinical depression|depression]], while others claim that it describes the difficult process of finding a reason to live in spite of depression and pain and does not have much to do with the storyline of ''The Downward Spiral''.<ref>Huxley (1997), p. 104</ref>\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video for Nine Inch Nails' original version of \"Hurt\" is a live performance that was recorded before the show in [[Omaha, Nebraska]], on February 13, 1995, and can be found on ''[[Closure (Nine Inch Nails VHS)|Closure]]'' and the [[DualDisc]] re-release of ''[[The Downward Spiral#DVD side|The Downward Spiral]]''. The audio portion appears on the UK version of ''[[Further Down the Spiral#UK version|Further Down the Spiral]]''.\nThe version released on ''[[Closure (Nine Inch Nails VHS)|Closure]]'' differs slightly from the video originally aired on MTV.  In addition to using an uncensored audio track, the ''[[Closure (Nine Inch Nails VHS)|Closure]]'' edit shows alternate views of the audience and performance at several points during the video.\n\nTo film the video, a [[Scrim (material)|scrim]] was dropped in front of the band on stage, onto which various images, such as [[war crime|war atrocities]], a [[nuclear bomb]] test, survivors of the [[Battle of Stalingrad]], a snake staring at the camera, and a [[time-lapse]] film of a fox decomposing in reverse, were projected, adding visual symbolism to fit the song's subject matter. A spotlight was cast on Reznor so that he can be seen through the images. Compared to the live renditions performed on future tours, this version most resembles the studio recording with its use of the song's original [[Sampling (music)|samples]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}}\n\nThere are also official live recordings on the later releases ''[[And All that Could Have Been]]'' and ''[[Beside You in Time]]''. Each version features distinct instrumentation by the varying members of the band in the respective eras.\n\n==Live performances==\nDuring the ''[[Outside Tour|Dissonance]]'' tour in 1995, when Nine Inch Nails opened for [[David Bowie]], Bowie sang \"Hurt\" in a duet with Reznor, backed by an original melody and beat. This served as the conclusion to the dual act that began each Bowie set.\n\nDuring the ''Fragility'' tours, the progression was performed by [[Robin Finck]] on [[acoustic guitar]] rather than on piano.\n\nSince the 2005\u201306 ''Live: With Teeth'' tour, Nine Inch Nails has been playing \"Hurt\" in a more toned-down style, featuring only Reznor on keyboard and vocals until the final chorus, when the rest of the band joins in.\n\nThe song was brought back to its original form during the ''Lights In The Sky'' tour in 2008, before returning to the toned down style on the 2009 ''Wave Goodbye'' tour.\n\n==Track listing==\n*'''US promotional CD single'''<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=\"Hurt\" |type=US promotional CD single |others=[[Nine Inch Nails]] |publisher=[[Interscope Records]] |year=1995 |id=PRCD 6179}}</ref>\n#\"Hurt\" (quiet version) {{small|(clean)}} \u2013 5:04\n#\"Hurt\" (live version) {{small|(clean)}} \u2013 5:15\n#\"Hurt\" (album version) {{small|(clean)}} \u2013 6:16\n#\"Hurt\" (quiet version) {{small|(soiled)}} \u2013 5:21\n#\"Hurt\" (live version) {{small|(soiled)}} \u2013 5:15\n#\"Hurt\" (album version) {{small|(soiled)}} \u2013 6:13\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Trent Reznor]] \u2013 [[lead vocalist|vocals]], [[guitar]], [[bass guitar]], [[piano]], [[synthesizer]]s\n* [[Chris Vrenna]] \u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1995)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br>position\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadarock|8|chartid=9238|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 25, 2016}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardradiosongs|54|artist=Nine Inch Nails|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 21, 2013}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardalternativesongs|8|artist=Nine Inch Nails|rowheader=true|accessdate=December 25, 2016}}\n|}\n\n==In popular culture==\n*The song was featured in the season two finale of the adult animated science fiction program [[Rick and Morty]], overlaying the series of events in which Rick surrenders to the intergalactic authorities, allowing his family to return to earth while simultaneously abandoning them.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sinacola |first=Dom |date=2015-12-17 |title=I Will Make You Hurt: Grief in Rick and Morty, The Leftovers and Heart of a Dog |URL=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/12/i-will-make-you-hurt-grief-in-rick-and-morty-the-l.html |work=Paste Magazine |access-date=2020-03-03</ref>\n\n==Johnny Cash version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Hurt\n| cover      = Johnny_Cash_-_Personal_Jesus_and_Hurt_single.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Johnny Cash]]\n| album      = [[American IV: The Man Comes Around]]\n| B-side     = {{hlist|\"[[Personal Jesus]]\"|\"[[Wichita Lineman]]\"}}\n| released   = March 2003\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2002\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Alternative rock]]<ref>[http://ajournalofmusicalthings.com/top-ten-most-depressing-alternative-rock-songs/ Top Ten Most Depressing Alternative Rock Songs] Retrieved January 5, 2015</ref>|{{nowrap|[[acoustic rock]]<ref>[http://www.planetrock.com/music/backstage/the-rock-lists/the-best-ever-acoustic-rock-song-the-top-40/ The Best Ever Acoustic Rock Songs: Top 40] Retrieved October 20, 2014</ref>}}|[[country music|country]]<ref>[http://www.ew.com/article/2008/04/07/johnny-cash-hur Johnny Cash's 'Hurt' still the greatest country video]<br>[[Entertainment Weekly]]<br>Retrieved August 9, 2016</ref>|{{nowrap|[[Southern gothic#Music|Southern gothic]]<ref>\n[https://books.google.com/books?id=pfkKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA209&lpg=PA209&dq=The+Man+Comes+Around+Southern+Gothic&source=bl&ots=890sdtyIMr&sig=SMudFaKrpxbvT5bNt5vt1O6pXoc&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjjroOWh8DdAhUhnuAKHeDuALk4ChDoATACegQIBxAB#v=onepage&q=The%20Man%20Comes%20Around%20Southern%20Gothic&f=false Walking the Line: Country Music Lyricists and American Culture] Retrieved September 16, 2018</ref>}}\n}}\n| length     = 3:38\n| label      = {{hlist|[[American Recordings (record label)|American]]|[[Lost Highway Records|Lost Highway]]}}\n| writer     = [[Trent Reznor]]\n| producer   = [[Rick Rubin]]\n| prev_title = [[The Man Comes Around (song)|The Man Comes Around]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[God's Gonna Cut You Down]]\n| next_year  = 2006\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|8AHCfZTRGiI|\"Hurt\"}}}}\n}}\n\nIn 2002, [[Johnny Cash]] covered the song for his album, ''[[American IV: The Man Comes Around]]''. Its accompanying video, featuring images from Cash's life and directed by [[Mark Romanek]], was named the best video of the year by the [[Grammy Award]]s and [[Country Music Association Awards|CMA Awards]], and the best video of all time by ''[[NME]]'' in July 2011.<ref name=NME>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/nme/57784 |title=NME names Johnny Cash's 'Hurt' the greatest music video of all time |newspaper=[[NME]] |date=July 5, 2011 |accessdate=December 27, 2011}}</ref> The single contains a cover of [[Depeche Mode]]'s \"[[Personal Jesus]]\" as a B-side.\n\nCash's cover of the song had sold 2,148,000 downloads in the United States as of March 2017.<ref name=\"Downloads\">{{cite news |url=http://roughstock.com/news/2017/03/41602-top-30-digital-single-sales-chart-march-22-2017 |title=Top 30 Digital Single Sales Chart: March 22, 2017 |first= Matt |last=Bjorke |date= March 22, 2017 |work=Roughstock }}</ref>\n\n===Background===\nWhen Reznor was asked if Cash could cover his song, Reznor said he was \"flattered\" but worried that \"the idea sounded a bit gimmicky.\" He became a fan of Cash's version, however, once he saw the music video.\n{{quote|I pop the video in, and wow... Tears welling, silence, goose-bumps... Wow. [I felt like] I just lost my girlfriend, because that song isn't mine anymore... It really made me think about how powerful music is as a medium and art form. I wrote some words and music in my bedroom as a way of staying sane, about a bleak and desperate place I was in, totally isolated and alone. [Somehow] that winds up reinterpreted by a music legend from a radically different era/genre and still retains sincerity and meaning&nbsp;\u2013 different, but every bit as pure.<ref>''[[Alternative Press (music magazine)|Alternative Press]]'' No. 194. September 2004.</ref>}}\n\n===Music video===\nThe music video was directed by former Nine Inch Nails collaborator [[Mark Romanek]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Director Mark Romanek Tackles 'Never Let Me Go'|newspaper=[[Fresh Air]]| date=September 23, 2010|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=130072068|accessdate=October 27, 2010}}</ref> who sought to capture the essence of Cash, both in his youth and in his older years. In a montage of shots of Cash's early years, twisted imagery of fruit and flowers in various states of decay, seem to capture both his legendary past and the stark and seemingly cruel reality of the present. According to literature professor Leigh H. Edwards, the music video portrays \"Cash's own paradoxical themes\".<ref name=\"paradox\"/>\n\nRomanek had this to say about his decision to focus on the [[House of Cash]] museum in Nashville:\n\n{{quote|It had been closed for a long time; the place was in such a state of dereliction. That's when I got the idea that maybe we could be extremely candid about the state of Johnny's health, as candid as Johnny has always been in his songs.<ref>{{cite news |last=Binelli  |first=Mark  |date=February 20, 2003 |title=Johnny Cash Makes 'Em Hurt |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/news/johnny-cash-makes-em-hurt-20030220#ixzz3xcOUwgiT  |newspaper=[[Rolling Stone]] |access-date=January 18, 2016 }}</ref>}}\n\nWhen the video was filmed in February 2003, Cash was 71 years old and had serious health problems. His frailty is clearly evident in the video. He died seven months later, on September 12;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stagepassnews.com/articles/vox/johnnycash_hurt.html |title=Johnny Cash, 'Hurt' & Trent Reznor |publisher=Stagepass News |date= |accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref> his wife, [[June Carter Cash]], who is shown gazing at her husband in two sequences of the video, died on May 15 of the same year.\n\nIn July 2011, the music video was named one of \"The 30 All-TIME Best Music Videos\" by ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=The 30 All-TIME Best Music Videos - Johnny Cash, Hurt|url=http://www.time.com/time/specials/packages/article/0,28804,2085389_2085359_2085375,00.html|work=Time|accessdate=August 19, 2011|first=Glen|last=Levy| date=July 28, 2011}}</ref> It was ranked the greatest music video of all time by ''[[NME]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=100 Greatest Music Videos|url=http://www.nme.com/list/100-greatest-music-videos/217342/page/10|publisher=NME|accessdate=December 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe house where Cash's music video for \"Hurt\" was shot, which was Cash's home for nearly 30 years, was destroyed in a fire on April 10, 2007.<ref>{{cite news|url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/6543503.stm|title=Fire destroys Johnny Cash home|accessdate=August 23, 2009|work=BBC News|date=April 11, 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Awards===\n*The Johnny Cash cover was given the [[Country Music Association]] award for \"Single of the Year\" in 2003. It ranked as [[CMT (U.S. TV channel)|CMT]]'s top video for 2003, No. 1 on CMT's 100 Greatest Country Music Videos the following year (and again in 2008), and No. 1 on the Top 40 Most Memorable Music Videos on [[MuchMore]]Music's ''Listed'' in October 2007. As of March 2016, the single occupies the number nine spot on [[Rate Your Music]]'s Top Singles of the 2000s.<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://rateyourmusic.com/charts/top/single/2000s| title = Top Singles of the 2000s\n| publisher = [[Rate Your Music]]| accessdate = September 17, 2009}}</ref> The song is also Cash's sole chart entry on the [[Alternative Songs|''Billboard'' Modern Rock Tracks]] chart, where it hit No. 33 in 2003.<ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=johnny cash|chart=all}} Billboard - Artist Chart History - Johnny Cash]</ref> In June 2009, the song was voted No. 1 in UpVenue's Top 10 Best Music Covers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upvenue.com/music-news/blog-headline/1058/top-10-best-music-covers.html|title= UpVenue's Top 10 Best Music Covers| accessdate = August 23, 2009}}</ref>\n*\"Hurt\" was nominated for six awards at the [[2003 MTV Video Music Awards]], winning for Best Cinematography.  With the video, Johnny Cash became the oldest artist ever nominated for an MTV Video Music Award.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.songstuff.com/article/johnny_cash_memories_shared/| title = Johnny Cash - Memories Shared | publisher = Songstuff| accessdate = June 27, 2013}}</ref> [[Justin Timberlake]], who won Best Male Video that year for \"[[Cry Me a River (Justin Timberlake song)|Cry Me a River]]\", said in his acceptance speech that the [[MTV Video Music Award]] for Best Male Video should have gone to Cash.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1478180/johnny-cash-remembered-by-justin-bono-trent-reznor-others/|title=mtv.com \"September 12, 2003 Johnny Cash Remembered By Justin, Bono, Trent Reznor, Others\"| accessdate = October 30, 2016}}</ref>\n*The music video won the 2004 [[Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video]].\n*In May 2010, 'Hurt' was voted the fifth most influential video of all time by [[MySpace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Michael-Jacksons-Thriller-Tops-Online-Groundbreaking-Music-Video-Poll-For-MySpace-UK/Article/201005115624057?f=rss |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120713062313/http://news.sky.com/skynews/Home/Showbiz-News/Michael-Jacksons-Thriller-Tops-Online-Groundbreaking-Music-Video-Poll-For-MySpace-UK/Article/201005115624057?f=rss |url-status=dead |archive-date=July 13, 2012 |title=Sky News 03/05/2010 |publisher=News.sky.com |accessdate=December 11, 2011 }}</ref>\n* In October 2011, ''[[NME]]'' placed it at number 35 on its list \"150 Best Tracks of the Past 15 Years\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/list/150-best-tracks-of-the-past-15-years/248648/page/12 |title=150 Best Tracks of the Past 15 Years |publisher=Nme.Com |date= |accessdate=December 11, 2011}}</ref>\n* In a 2014 survey conducted by the [[BBC]] the UK public voted the Johnny Cash version the second greatest cover version of all time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-29791820|title=Pet Shop Boys' Always On My Mind tops cover version vote|publisher=BBC News|date=27 October 2014|accessdate=2018-12-10}}</ref>\n\n===In popular culture===\n*The Johnny Cash version has appeared in several films, documentaries and TV shows including ''[[Colombiana]]'', ''[[Criminal Minds]]'', ''[[Smallville]]'', ''[[Inside I'm Dancing]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0417791/soundtrack|title=Inside I'm Dancing (2004) Soundtracks|date=October 15, 2004|publisher=|via=IMDb}}</ref> ''[[Person of Interest (TV series)|Person of Interest]]'' and ''[[Why We Fight (2005 film)|Why We Fight]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0143599/|title=Johnny Cash|publisher=}}</ref> in addition to the teaser trailer for the [[Marvel Entertainment|Marvel]] film ''[[Logan (film)|Logan]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spin.com/2016/10/wolverine-logan-trailer-hugh-jackman-patrick-stewart/|title=Johnny Cash Soundtracks First Trailer for the Depressing New Wolverine Movie - SPIN|date=October 20, 2016|publisher=}}</ref> [[James Mangold]], the director of ''Logan'' had previously directed the Johnny Cash biopic ''[[Walk the Line]]''. The song does not appear in the film proper, with the film instead opting to use Cash's \"[[The Man Comes Around]]\" over the ending credits.\n*[[ITV Sport]] used this version in a montage of England's exit from the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] after losing a penalty shoot out against Portugal. One montage scene showed [[David Beckham]] visibly shaken and emotional for not being able to play due to an injury during the match, being in tears at one point .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2006/SPORT/football/07/01/worldcup.portugal/|title=Portugal sink England on Penalties|publisher=|accessdate=September 12, 2014}}</ref>\n*[[Sky Sports]] also used a section of this version in a montage of the [[2013\u201314 Ashes series]] following England's 5-0 defeat by Australia.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GWDh94O0KWw|title=Sky Ashes Montage 2013/14|first=|last=matt smith|date=January 7, 2014|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n*During the edition of November 14, 2005 of ''[[WWE Raw]]'', [[WWE]] used the song for their tribute show dedicated to [[Eddie Guerrero]] following his death from heart failure.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IOHgpmNj0Zw|title=Eddie Guerrero Tribute Show in RAW part 1|first=|last=Theundertakerfan85|date=October 19, 2009|publisher=|via=YouTube}}</ref>\n\n===Track listing===\n*'''European CD single'''\n#\"Hurt\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:38\n#\"[[Personal Jesus]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:21\n#\"[[Wichita Lineman]]\"&nbsp;\u2013 3:06\n#\"Hurt\" (music video)\n\n===Charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable 