Acoustic Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/southside-double-wide-acoustic-live-mw0000339599 | title=Sevendust - Southside Double-Wide: Acoustic Live | publisher=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=January 3, 2016 | author=Loftus, Johnny}}</ref>\n* [[Eddie Vedder]] made a live cover version in 2008, referencing it as \"borrowed from Chicago\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.reddit.com/r/pearljam/comments/5v9x3r/pearl_jam_covering_jonny_cash_hurt/?sort=new | title=Pearl Jam covering Jonny Cash - Hurt (m.youtube.com)| publisher= | accessdate=April 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MPyvNUwhQoI</ref>\n* [[Leona Lewis]] covered the song on her 2011 EP, ''[[Hurt: The EP]]''.\n* The cello duo [[2Cellos]] released a rendition of the song on its [[2Cellos (album)|self-titled 2011 album]], based on Johnny Cash's version.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/2cellos-mw0002157361 | title=2Cellos - 2Cellos | publisher=[[Allmusic]] | accessdate=January 3, 2016 | author=O'Brien, Jon}}</ref>\n* 2012 [[Lucinda Williams]] covered the Cash version of the song in the concert and accompanying live album [[We Walk the Line]].\n*[[Eric Whitacre]] wrote a choral version of the song, composed in 2013-14 and released as a single in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://ericwhitacre.com/blog/hurt|title=Hurt|date=2013-12-02|work=Eric Whitacre|access-date=2018-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Eric Whitacre and Eric Whitacre Singers|title=Hurt|url=https://www.amazon.com/Hurt/dp/B076ZV9SFP|access-date=2018-09-28}}</ref>\n* 2019 [[Mumford & Sons]] performed a cover version as a ballad in their show at Quicken Loans Arena in Cleveland, Ohio, Trent Reznor's origin city.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.musikexpress.de/video-mumford-sons-covern-nine-inch-nails-hurt-1209477/ |title=Video: Mumford & Sons covern Nine Inch Nails \u201eHurt\u201c  |date= 2019-03-11  |access-date=2019-03-21}}</ref>\n* 2019 [[The Hospital for Sick Children, Toronto|SickKids]] used a version of the song but it was sung by children. This video was released for this campaign on Oct 10 2019. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/8p6qkHvHQB0|title=Video: Sickkids VS: This Is Why [Special Edit] |date= 2019-10-10|}} </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{cite book\n| url = https://archive.org/details/lillustrecompig00frgoog\n| title = Johnny Cash and the Paradox of American Identity\n| last = Edwards\n| first = Leigh H.\n| publisher = [[Indiana University Press]]\n| isbn=0253220610\n| year=2009\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news\n |url=http://kdka.com/topstories/Virginia.Tech.convocation.2.282556.html \n |title=Digital Tributes Honor Virginia Tech Victims \n |work=[[KDKA-TV]] \n |date=April 18, 2007 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071222132159/http://kdka.com/topstories/Virginia.Tech.convocation.2.282556.html \n |archivedate=December 22, 2007 \n |df=mdy \n}}\n* {{cite news\n| url = https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/7378167/in_other_words_trent_reznor\n| title = In Other Words: Trent Reznor\n| author = [[Anthony DeCurtis]]\n| work = [[Rolling Stone]]\n| date = June 7, 2005\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{YouTube|dhh21crSohs|NiN 1995 live concert video}}\n* {{YouTube|8AHCfZTRGiI|Johnny Cash - Hurt 2003 official music video}}\n* {{Discogs release|id=232407|name=Hurt}}\n* {{MetroLyrics song|nine-inch-nails|hurt}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Nine Inch Nails}}\n{{Johnny Cash|song}}\n{{Leona Lewis}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hurt (Nine Inch Nails Song)}}\n[[Category:1990s ballads]]\n[[Category:1994 songs]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:American Recordings (record label) singles]]\n[[Category:Gothic rock songs]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award for Best Short Form Music Video]]\n[[Category:Johnny Cash songs]]\n[[Category:Music videos directed by Mark Romanek]]\n[[Category:Nine Inch Nails songs]]\n[[Category:Self-harm in fiction]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Flood (producer)]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Rick Rubin]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Songs about heroin]]\n[[Category:Songs about suicide]]\n[[Category:Songs about depression]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Rock ballads]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIn popular culture:format cite template", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hurt_(Nine_Inch_Nails_song)"}
{"title_page": "Deyen Lawson", "text_new": "{{copy edit|reason=Excessive images which do not add to article. Punctuation and formatting needs polishing. |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = Deyen Lawson\n| image             = Deyen Lawson and Allison Orchard.jpg\n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = Deyen Lawson and partner (professional golfer Allison Orchard)\n| fullname          = Deyen Mitchell Lawson\n| nickname          = Digger\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1991|1|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Geelong]], [[Victoria]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1986|2|9|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = {{height|m=1.87|precision=0}}\n| nationality       = {{AUS}}\n| residence         = [[Gold Coast]], [[Australia]]\n| spouse            = \n| partner           = Ali Orchard (engaged)\n| yearpro           = 2016\n| tour              = [[European Tour]]<br/>[[PGA Tour of Australasia]]\n| extour            = [[China Tour]]\n}}\n[[File:Deyen Lawson Perth Open 2019.jpg|thumb|Deyen Lawson and caddie Jonathan Clark-Howard ISPS Handa World Super 6 Perth\nFeb 2019]]\n\n'''Deyen Michell (Digger) Lawson''' (born 4 January 1991) is an [[Australia]]n [[professional golfer]] currently playing on the [[European Tour]] and [[PGA Tour of Australasia]]. Lawson starting playing golf at the age of 10. He commenced a golf professional traineeship in 2014 at Curlewis Golf Club in Geelong Australia. <ref name=Lawson>{{cite web |url=http://www.cgatour.com.cn/en/golf/player_detail.do?id=61259|title=Deyen Lawson|publisher=CGA Tour |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nHaving completed his golf teaching traineeship at Curlewis Golf Club Victoria Australia, Lawson earned a place on the [[PGA Tour of Australasia]] in 2016. In 2018 he attended the European Tour Qualifying Tour school for the second time. Lawson finished tied thirteen at the final stage at the [[2018_European_Tour_Qualifying_School_graduates]] gaining a full time playing card for 2019 season. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/final-qualifying-stage-lumine-2018/results?round=6 |title=Final Qualifying Stage Lumine 2018 |publisher=European Tour |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of his debut season on the European Tour He had the unusual achievement of two holes in one. The first happened at [[Alfred Dunhill Championship]] in December 2018. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/news/video/deyen-lawson-hole-in-one-at-alfred-dunhill-championship/ |title=Deyen Lawson hole-in-one at Alfred Dunhill Championship|publisher=European Tour |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://aussiegolfer.com.au/aussie-digger-lawson-snags-hole-in-one-and-a-250k-bmw/ |title=Aussie Digger Lawson snags hole-in-one and a $250k BMW|publisher=Aussie Golfer |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> For his effort Lawson won a BMW 8 Series worth around $250,000. [[File:Deyen Lawson wins bmw 850i Dunhill Championship 2018.jpg|thumb|Deyen Lawson wins BMW 850i Alfred Dunhill Championship 2018]] The second ace came at the [[Commercial Bank Qatar Masters]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/11658645/deyen-lawson-fires-second-hole-in-one-of-season-at-qatar-masters |title=Deyen Lawson fires second hole-in-one of season at Qatar Masters|publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> Both holes Lawson used his eight iron. \n\nFrom late September 2018 to April 2019 Deyen Lawson had caddie Jonathan (jono) Clark-Howard on his bag.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pga.org.au/news/deyen-lawson-the-putt-that-changed-everything/ |title=Deyen Lawson: The putt that changed everything|publisher=PGA Australia |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hhaMMT3NyM0&feature=youtu.be|title=Jonathan Clark-Howard Caddie|publisher=Ish Cheyne |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/new-zealand-golf-magazine/20190401/281900184571426|title=On the Bag with Jonathan Clark-Howard |publisher=New Zealand Golf Magazine |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nLawson finished 187 on the European Tour Race to Dubai rankings for 2019. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/rankings/race-to-dubai/rankings/2019/|title=Race to Dubai 2019 |publisher=European Tour |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>. He returned to European Tour q school and gained limited playing membership rights (Exemption Category 22) for the 2020 season by making the cut at the final stage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/players/exemption-categories/|title=Exemption Categories 2020 |publisher=European Tour |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nLawson finished 17 on the ISPS HANDA PGA Tour of Australasia 2019 order of merit from just six starts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pga.org.au/oom/?class=aus|title=ISPS HANDA PGA Tour of Australasia 2019 |publisher=PGA Tour Australia |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> This included two top 10 finishes T2 at the Queensland PGA championship and T10 at the Australian Open championship. \n \n[[File:Deyen Lawson and Caddie Jono Clark Howard - Dunhill Championship 2018.jpg|thumb|Deyen Lawson practice at Alfred Dunhill Championship Leopard Creek South Africa 2018]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{EuroTour player|41012}}\n*{{PGATour player|28938}}\n*{{OWGR|15885}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lawson, Deyen}\n[[Category:Australian male golfers]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{copy edit|reason=Excessive images which do not add to article. Punctuation and formatting needs polishing. |date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = Deyen Lawson\n| image             = Deyen Lawson and Allison Orchard.jpg\n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = Deyen Lawson and partner (professional golfer Allison Orchard)\n| fullname          = Deyen Mitchell Lawson\n| nickname          = Digger\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|1991|1|7|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Geelong]], [[Victoria]], [[Australia]]\n| death_date        = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|1986|2|9|df=y}} -->\n| death_place       = \n| height            = {{height|m=1.87|precision=0}}\n| nationality       = {{AUS}}\n| residence         = [[Gold Coast]], [[Australia]]\n| spouse            = \n| partner           = Ali Orchard (engaged)\n| yearpro           = 2016\n| tour              = [[European Tour]]<br/>[[PGA Tour of Australasia]]\n| extour            = [[China Tour]]\n}}\n[[File:Deyen Lawson Perth Open 2019.jpg|thumb|Deyen Lawson and caddie Jonathan Clark-Howard ISPS Handa World Super 6 Perth\nFeb 2019]]\n\n'''Deyen Michell (Digger) Lawson''' (born 4 January 1991) is an [[Australia]]n [[professional golfer]] currently playing on the [[European Tour]] and [[PGA Tour of Australasia]]. Lawson starting playing the golf at the age of 10. He commenced a golf professional traineeship in 2014 at Curlewis Golf Club in Geelong Australia. <ref name=Lawson>{{cite web |url=http://www.cgatour.com.cn/en/golf/player_detail.do?id=61259|title=Deyen Lawson|publisher=CGA Tour |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nHaving completed his golf teaching traineeship at Curlewis Golf Club Victoria Australia, Lawson earned a place on the [[PGA Tour of Australasia]] in 2016. In 2018 he attended the European Tour Qualifying Tour school for the second time. Lawson finished tied thirteen at the final stage at the [[2018_European_Tour_Qualifying_School_graduates]] gaining a full time playing card for 2019 season. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/final-qualifying-stage-lumine-2018/results?round=6 |title=Final Qualifying Stage Lumine 2018 |publisher=European Tour |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the first half of his debut season on the European Tour He had the unusual achievement of two holes in one. The first happened at [[Alfred Dunhill Championship]] in December 2018. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/news/video/deyen-lawson-hole-in-one-at-alfred-dunhill-championship/ |title=Deyen Lawson hole-in-one at Alfred Dunhill Championship|publisher=European Tour |accessdate=1 January 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://aussiegolfer.com.au/aussie-digger-lawson-snags-hole-in-one-and-a-250k-bmw/ |title=Aussie Digger Lawson snags hole-in-one and a $250k BMW|publisher=Aussie Golfer |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> For his effort Lawson won a BMW 8 Series worth around $250,000. [[File:Deyen Lawson wins bmw 850i Dunhill Championship 2018.jpg|thumb|Deyen Lawson wins BMW 850i Alfred Dunhill Championship 2018]] The second ace came at the [[Commercial Bank Qatar Masters]] in March 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/golf/news/12176/11658645/deyen-lawson-fires-second-hole-in-one-of-season-at-qatar-masters |title=Deyen Lawson fires second hole-in-one of season at Qatar Masters|publisher=Sky Sports |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> Both holes Lawson used his eight iron. \n\nFrom late September 2018 to April 2019 Deyen Lawson had caddie Jonathan (jono) Clark-Howard on his bag.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pga.org.au/news/deyen-lawson-the-putt-that-changed-everything/ |title=Deyen Lawson: The putt that changed everything|publisher=PGA Australia |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hhaMMT3NyM0&feature=youtu.be|title=Jonathan Clark-Howard Caddie|publisher=Ish Cheyne |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pressreader.com/new-zealand/new-zealand-golf-magazine/20190401/281900184571426|title=On the Bag with Jonathan Clark-Howard |publisher=New Zealand Golf Magazine |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nLawson finished 187 on the European Tour Race to Dubai rankings for 2019. <ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/rankings/race-to-dubai/rankings/2019/|title=Race to Dubai 2019 |publisher=European Tour |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>. He returned to European Tour q school and gained limited playing membership rights (Exemption Category 22) for the 2020 season by making the cut at the final stage.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.europeantour.com/european-tour/players/exemption-categories/|title=Exemption Categories 2020 |publisher=European Tour |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nLawson finished 17 on the ISPS HANDA PGA Tour of Australasia 2019 order of merit from just six starts.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pga.org.au/oom/?class=aus|title=ISPS HANDA PGA Tour of Australasia 2019 |publisher=PGA Tour Australia |accessdate=2 January 2020}}</ref> This included two top 10 finishes T2 at the Queensland PGA championship and T10 at the Australian Open championship. \n \n[[File:Deyen Lawson and Caddie Jono Clark Howard - Dunhill Championship 2018.jpg|thumb|Deyen Lawson practice at Alfred Dunhill Championship Leopard Creek South Africa 2018]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{EuroTour player|41012}}\n*{{PGATour player|28938}}\n*{{OWGR|15885}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lawson, Deyen}\n[[Category:Australian male golfers]]\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Llunnaz", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deyen_Lawson"}
{"title_page": "Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show)", "text_new": "{{for|the current season|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show, season 21)}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Who Wants to Be a Millionaire\n| image                    = File:WWTBAMUS2020Logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Game show]]\n| developer                = [[Michael Davies (television producer)|Michael Davies]]\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Gentile <small>(1999\u20132002)</small>\n* Matthew Cohen <small>(2002\u201310)</small>\n* Rob George <small>(2010\u201313)</small>\n* Brian McAloon <small>(2013\u201314)</small>\n* Rich DiPirro <small>(2014\u201317)</small>\n* [[Ron de Moraes]] <small>(2017\u201319)</small>\n}}\n| presenter                = {{Plainlist|\n* ''ABC'':\n* [[Regis Philbin]]\n* [[Jimmy Kimmel]]\n* ''Syndication'':\n* [[Meredith Vieira]]\n* {{nowrap|[[Cedric the Entertainer]]}}\n* [[Terry Crews]]\n* [[Chris Harrison]]\n}}\n| country                  = United States\n| num_seasons              = 21 <small>(3 on ABC, 17 in syndication, 1 upcoming)</small>\n| num_episodes             = ''ABC'': 363<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n| composer                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Keith Strachan]] <small>(1999\u20132010, 2020\u2013present)</small><ref name=\"Matthew Strachan | Songwriter & Composer\">http://www.matthewstrachan.co.uk/credits.html</ref>\n* [[Matthew Strachan]] <small>(1999\u20132010, 2020\u2013present)</small><ref name=\"Matthew Strachan | Songwriter & Composer\"/>\n* Jeff Lippencott <small>(2010\u20132019)</small>\n* Mark T. Williams <small>(2010\u20132019)</small>\n}}\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Michael Davies (television producer)|Michael Davies]] <small>(1999\u20132010, 2020\u2013present)</small>\n* Paul Smith <small>(1999\u20132007)</small>\n* Leigh Hampton <small>(2004\u201310)</small>\n* Rich Sirop <small>(2010\u201314)</small>\n* James Rowley <small>(2014\u20132019)</small>\n}}\n| company                  = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Valleycrest Productions]] <small>(1999\u2013present)</small>\n* [[Celador]] <small>(1999\u20132007)</small>\n* [[2waytraffic]] <small>(2007\u20132019)</small>\n* [[Embassy Row (production company)|Embassy Row]] <small>(2020\u2013present)</small><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.embassyrow.com/productions/who-wants-be-millionaire|title=Who Wants to Be A Millionaire|work=[[Embassy Row (production company)|Embassy Row]]|accessdate=March 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* Kimmelot <small>(2020\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| runtime                  = 39\u201348 minutes (ABC)<br>19\u201325 minutes (syndication) <!-- Runtimes do not count commercials. -->\n| distributor              = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Disney-ABC Domestic Television|Buena Vista Television]]<br><small>(1999\u20132007)</small>\n* [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]<br><small>(2007\u20132015)</small>\n* [[Disney-ABC Domestic Television|Disney-ABC Home Entertainment and Television Distribution]]<br><small>(2015\u2013present)</small>\n}}\n| network                  = [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] <small>(1999\u20132002, 2004, 2009, 2020\u2013present)</small><br>[[Broadcast syndication|Syndication]] <small>(2002\u20132019)</small>\n| picture_format           = [[480i]] ([[SDTV]]) <small>(1999\u20132011)</small><br>[[720p]]/[[1080i]] ([[HDTV]]) <small>(2011\u2013present)</small>\n| audio_format             = [[Stereo]]\n| first_aired              = ''ABC'':<br>{{Start date|1999|8|16}} \u2013 {{End date|2002|6|27}} <br> {{Start date|2020|4|8}} \u2013 present<br>''Syndication'':<br>{{Start date|2002|9|16}} \u2013 {{End date|2019|5|31}}\n| last_aired               = \n}}\n'''''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''''' (often informally called '''''Millionaire'''''{{refn|The simplified title was often used by hosts and in promotional materials.|group=note}}) is an American television [[game show]] based on the [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? (British game show)|same-titled British program]] and developed for the United States by [[Michael Davies (television producer)|Michael Davies]]. The show features a [[quiz]] competition in which contestants attempt to win a top prize of $1,000,000 by answering a series of multiple-choice questions of increasing difficulty (although, for a time, most of the questions were of random difficulty). The program endured as one of the longest-running and most successful international variants in the ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' franchise, running continuously in some form since 1999.\n\nThe original U.S. version premiered on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] on August 16, 1999 as part of a two-week daily special event hosted by [[Regis Philbin]]. After this and a second two-week event aired in November 1999, ABC commissioned a regular series that launched on January 18, 2000 and ran until June 27, 2002. Philbin hosted the entire run of the original network series as well as three additional special event series that aired on ABC in 2004 and 2009. \n\nA daily version of ''Millionaire'' produced for [[Broadcast syndication|syndication]] began airing on September 16, 2002, and was initially hosted by [[Meredith Vieira]]. [[Cedric the Entertainer]] took over the show in 2013 following Vieira's departure, with [[Terry Crews]] replacing him in 2014. The syndicated series' final host was [[Chris Harrison]], who took over from Crews in 2015 and hosted until the show was ultimately cancelled, with the finale airing on May 31, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|last=Otterson|first=Joe|title='Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' to End After 17 Years in Syndication (Exclusive)|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-canceled-1203217602/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=May 17, 2019|accessdate=June 27, 2019}}</ref> \nOn January 8, 2020, seven months after the cancellation was announced, ABC renewed the show for a [[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show, season 21)|twenty-first season]] (consisting of eight episodes) that would be hosted by [[Jimmy Kimmel]] and feature celebrity contestants; the twenty-first season premiered on April 8, 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/jimmy-kimmel-host-celebrity-driven-who-wants-be-a-millionaire-abc-1268004|title=Jimmy Kimmel to Host Celebrity-Driven 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' for ABC|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=January 8, 2020|accessdate=January 8, 2020}}</ref> On April 12, 2020, ABC renewed Millionaire for a twenty-second season with a premiere date yet to be announced. [https://twitter.com/MillionaireTV/status/1249381769050075141 Millionaire renewed for new season]\n\nAs the first U.S. network game show to offer a million-dollar top prize, the show made television history by becoming one of the highest-rated game shows in the history of American television. The U.S. ''Millionaire'' won seven [[Daytime Emmy Award]]s, and ''[[TV Guide]]'' ranked it No. 6 in its 2013 list of the 60 greatest game shows of all time.\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Gameplay==\n===Core rules===\n[[File:Wales on millionaire.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Screenshot illustrating how question text and answer choices appear on-screen]]\nAt its core, the game is a quiz competition in which the goal is to correctly answer a series of fourteen (originally fifteen) consecutive multiple-choice questions. The questions are of increasing difficulty,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.millionairetv.com/rules.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020705162039/http://www.millionairetv.com/rules.html|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Syndicated Version original rules|date=June 28, 2002|publisher=Valleycrest Productions, Ltd. and Buena Vista Television|archivedate=July 5, 2002}}</ref> except in the 2010\u201315 format overhaul, where the contestants were faced with a round of ten questions of random difficulty, followed by a round of four questions of increasing difficulty.<ref name=\"millionairetv\">{{cite web|url=http://millionairetv.dadt.com/official-rules-season-13/ |title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Official Rules (Season 13) |publisher=dadt.com |accessdate=July 19, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222225725/http://millionairetv.dadt.com/official-rules/ |archivedate=December 22, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Each question is worth a specified amount of money; the amounts are cumulative in the first round, but not in the second. If at any time the contestant gives a wrong answer, the game is over and the contestant's winnings are reduced (or increased, in the first two questions) to $1,000 for tier-one questions, $5,000 for tier-two questions, and $50,000 for tier-three questions. However, the contestant may choose to stop playing after being presented with a question, allowing them to keep all the money they have won to that point.<ref name=\"millionairetv\"/> With the exception of the shuffle format, upon correctly answering questions five and ten, contestants are guaranteed at least the amount of prize money associated with that level. If the contestant gives an incorrect answer, their winnings drop down to the last milestone achieved. Since 2015, if the contestant answers a question incorrectly before reaching question five, he or she leaves with $1,000, even on the first question that is worth only $500. For celebrities, the minimum guarantee for their nominated charities is $10,000. Prior to the shuffle format, a contestant left with nothing if they answered a question incorrectly before reaching the first milestone. In the shuffle format, contestants who incorrectly answered a question had their winnings reduced to $1,000 in round one and $25,000 in round two.<ref name=\"Millionaire Facebook\u20142010 changes\">{{cite press release|url= https://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/network-press-releases/syndicated-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-premieres-new-season-september-13/|title=Syndicated ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' Premieres New Season September 13|author= Disney-ABC Domestic Television|work=[[TV by the Numbers]]|publisher=Zap2it|date=August 16, 2010|accessdate=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Format history ===\n==== Original format (1999\u20132008; since 2020) ====\nFrom 1999 to 2002, 10 contestants played a round of Fastest Finger to determine who would play in the hot seat. The participants would be confronted with one question and four answers, and they would have to set the four answers in the correct order (ascending, chronological, etc.) in the fastest time. The competitor who did so correctly in the fastest time would play. If nobody got the correct order, the round was played again, and when a tie breaker occurred, the remaining participants answered a second Fastest Finger question. This round was removed when the syndicated version began in 2002, though it returned in 2004 for Super Millionaire and in 2009 for the 10th Anniversary shows, in which it was removed again in the 2020 reboot. The format remained unchanged, except for changes to the money staircase and the addition of a new lifeline, until 2008. In the 2020 reboot, a new lifeline was added called \"Ask The Host\", in which the host, Jimmy Kimmel, gives the player the best possible answer and some advice.\n\n====Clock format (2008\u20132010)====\nIn 2008, the format was altered to include a time limit on each question. The amount of time for each question was as follows:\n* Questions 1\u20135 '''($500-$5,000):''' 15 seconds\n* Questions 6\u201310 '''($7,500-$25,000):''' 30 seconds\n* Questions 11\u201314 '''($50,000-$500,000):''' 45 seconds\n* Question 15 '''($1,000,000 question):''' 45 seconds, plus the total of all unused time from the previous 14 questions\n\nThe timer began to run as soon as the four answer options were revealed, and the contestant had to give a final answer before it reached 0. \n\nIf time ran out, the game ended and the contestant left with whatever money they had won to that point. If this happened while the Double Dip lifeline was in effect, the contestant's winnings were instead reduced to the last safe haven they had reached.\n\nWhile the clock format was in use, the contestant was shown the categories of all 15 questions in the order they would be asked.\n\n====Shuffle format (2010\u20132015)====\nThe format was overhauled in September 2010, splitting the game into two rounds. The first round consisted of 10 questions, each in a different category and worth a different amount from $100 to $25,000. Both the category order and the amounts were randomized at the start of the game, with the latter hidden from the contestant's view. The difficulty level and value of each question were not tied to one another. The value of each question was revealed only after the contestant answered it correctly or chose to \"jump\" (skip) it; a correct answer added the money to the contestant's bank, while a jump put the value out of play. The maximum bank from this round was $68,600. If the contestant missed a question in the first round, they left with $1,000, even if their bank was lower than this total. Choosing to stop allowed the contestant to keep half their bank.\n\nThe second round presented four questions of increasing difficulty in the traditional format, each of which augmented the contestant's total winnings to a set value. A miss in this round reduced their winnings to $25,000. Categories for these questions were not given ahead of time.\n\nFrom 2011\u20132014, some weeks were \"Double Your Money\" weeks, in which one first-round question was randomly designated as being worth double value. The maximum potential bank from this round thus became $93,600.\n\n====Final format (2015\u20132019)====\nWith the hiring of new host Chris Harrison, the format was changed once again to resemble that of the original ''Millionaire''. Each contestant faces 14 general-knowledge questions of increasing difficulty, with no time limit or information about the categories. Beginning in 2017, a contestant who missed any of the first five questions left with $1,000, even if the missed question was of a lower value.\n\n===Payout structure===\nFive different ladders have been used over the course of the series:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"  style=\"text-align:center; width:50%;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:10%;\"|Question<br>number\n!colspan=\"5\"|Question value\n|-\n! style=\"width:18%\"|1999\u20132004, 2020\u2013\n! style=\"width:18%;\"|2004\u201309\n! style=\"width:18%;\"|2009\u201310\n! style=\"width:18%;\"|2010\u201315<ref name=\"Millionaire Facebook\u20142010 changes\"/>\n! style=\"width:18%;\"|2015\u201319\n|-\n|1\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$100\n|$500\n| rowspan=\"10\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<small>Random values</small><br>$100, $500, $1,000, $2,000, $3,000, $5,000, $7,000, $10,000, $15,000, and $25,000\n|$500\n|-\n|2\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$200\n|$1,000\n|$1,000\n|-\n|3\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$300\n|$2,000\n|$2,000\n|-\n|4\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$500\n|$3,000\n|$3,000\n|-\n|5\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''$1,000'''\n|'''$5,000'''\n|'''$5,000'''\n|-\n|6\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$2,000\n|$7,500\n|$7,000\n|-\n|7\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$4,000\n|$10,000\n|$10,000\n|-\n|8\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$8,000\n|$12,500\n|$20,000\n|-\n|9\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$16,000\n|$15,000\n|$30,000\n|-\n|10\n|'''$32,000'''\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''$25,000'''\n|'''$50,000'''\n|-\n|11\n|$64,000\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$50,000\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$100,000\n|-\n|12\n|$125,000\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$100,000\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$250,000\n|-\n|13\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$250,000\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$500,000\n|-\n|14\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|$500,000\n| colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''$1,000,000'''\n|-\n|15\n| colspan=\"3\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|'''$1,000,000'''\n|  colspan=\"2\" style=\"background:#c9cac8;\"|\n|}\n\nThe $500,000 and $1,000,000 prizes were initially lump-sum payments, but were changed to annuities in September 2002 when the series moved to syndication. Contestants winning either of these prizes receive $250,000 thirty days after their show broadcasts and the remainder paid in equal annual payments. The $500,000 prize consists of $25,000 per year for 10 years, while the $1,000,000 prize consists of $37,500 per year for 20 years, all less taxes.<ref name=\"millionairetv\"/>\n\nFrom 2017\u20132019, contestants who answered one of the first five questions incorrectly received a $1,000 consolation prize.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Wants To Be A Millionaire: Official Rules (Archive)|url=http://millionairetv.dadt.com/official-rules/|accessdate=24 July 2017|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170629022556/http://millionairetv.dadt.com/official-rules/|archivedate=June 29, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> On the original primetime version and in earlier seasons of the syndicated version prior to 2010, contestants who missed one of the first five questions left with no winnings.\n\n===Lifelines===\nForms of assistance known as \"lifelines\" are available for a contestant to use if a question proves difficult. Multiple lifelines may be used on a single question, but each one can only be used once per game (unless otherwise noted below). Three lifelines are available from the start of the game. Depending on the format of the show, additional lifelines may become available after the contestant correctly answers the fifth or tenth question. In the clock format, usage of lifelines temporarily pauses the clock while the lifelines are played.\n*'''+1''' (2014\u20132019): The contestant may invite a friend onstage from the audience to assist with the current question. After the question result, the friend must return to the audience.\n*'''50:50''' (1999\u20132008, 2015\u20132019; 2020): Two incorrect answers are eliminated, leaving the contestant with a choice between the correct answer and one remaining incorrect answer.\n*'''Ask the Audience''' (1999\u20132019): The audience members individually use four-button keypads to register the answer they believe is correct. The percentage of votes for each answer is immediately shown to the host, contestant, and home viewer. Beginning in 2004 and ending a few years later, [[AIM (software)|AIM]] users who added the screen name MillionaireIM to their buddy list and were online were able to receive and register answers they believed to be correct to Ask the Audience questions in real-time; these results were then shown as a separate chart to the contestant.<ref>https://www.adweek.com/brand-marketing/buena-vista-aol-make-millionaire-interactive-74453/</ref> \n*'''Ask the Expert''' (2008\u20132010): Based on Three Wise Men, the lifeline was earned after answering five questions correctly until 2010, when it was given to the contestant immediately following the removal of Phone a Friend. The contestant was connected to an expert via a video call via [[Skype]], and the two could discuss the question with no time limit.\n*'''Crystal Ball''' (2012\u20132015): Used occasionally during the \"shuffle\" round, this lifeline allowed the contestant to see the value of the current question before either answering or jumping it (if Jump the Question had not yet been used).\n*'''Double Dip''' (2004, 2008\u20132010): First used during ''Super Millionaire'', this lifeline allowed a contestant to make a second guess at the answer if his/her first one was wrong. The contestant had to invoke the lifeline before making the first guess, and it was removed from play regardless of which guess was correct. In addition, the contestant could not walk away from the question after invoking the lifeline. It was introduced to the main series in 2008, replacing 50:50.\n*'''Jump the Question''' (2010\u20132015): This lifeline allowed the contestant to skip the current question, but the money associated with it was removed from play. It could be used twice per game from 2010\u20132014, but only once from 2014\u20132015.\n*'''Phone a Friend''' (1999\u20132010; 2020): The contestant called a pre-arranged friend (via [[AT&T]] in ABC airings, except for ''Super Millionaire'' airings, until 2009) and was then given 30 seconds to discuss the question with that person. In 2010, this lifeline was eliminated due to an increasing use of search engines by home viewers to look up answers.<ref>{{cite web |last1=McGee |first1=Matt |title=How Google Killed \"Phone A Friend\" From \"Who Wants To Be A Millionaire?\" |url=https://searchengineland.com/how-google-killed-phone-a-friend-52624 |website=Search Engine Land |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n*'''Switch/Cut the Question''' (2004\u20132008): Earned after answering 10 questions, this lifeline allowed a contestant to discard the current question and replace it with one of the same value. It has been used occasionally during Whiz Kids Week in the current version and is available from the outset.\n*'''Three Wise Men''' (2004): Used during ''Super Millionaire'', this lifeline allowed the contestant 30 seconds of advice from a panel of three experts, who were sequestered backstage and saw the question only when their help was requested.\n*'''Ask the Host''' (2020): Introduced during the 2020 season, this lifeline allows the contestant to ask for the host's advice on the current question and give the best possible answer.\n* The 2020 season features a lifeline similar to +1. This lifeline is offered to the contestant after the tenth question and allows them to consult with their accompanying supporter one time during the final five questions. However, in order to obtain this lifeline, the contestant must exchange one of his or her other remaining lifelines. (The contestant has unlimited access to their supporter for the first ten questions.)\n\n===Top prize winners===\nOver the course of the program's history, twelve people answered the final question correctly and walked away with the top prize:  \n*[[John Carpenter (game show contestant)|John Carpenter]] \u2013 Became the first winner of the top prize on November 19, 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Taxman scoops a million|work=BBC News|date=November 21, 1999 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/529186.stm|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=PeopleMillionaires>{{cite magazine |url=http://people.com/archive/millionaire-makeovers-vol-54-no-20/|title=Millionaire Makeovers!|work=People|publisher=Time Inc.|volume=54 |number=20|date=November 13, 2000|accessdate=July 8, 2015}}</ref>\n*Dan Blonsky \u2013 Won on January 18, 2000.<ref name=PeopleMillionaires/>\n*Joe Trela \u2013 Won on  March 23, 2000.<ref name=PeopleMillionaires/>\n*Bob House \u2013 Won on June 13, 2000.<ref name=PeopleMillionaires/>\n*Kim Hunt \u2013 Won on July 6, 2000.<ref name=PeopleMillionaires/>\n*David Goodman \u2013 Won on July 11, 2000.<ref name=PeopleMillionaires/>\n*Kevin Olmstead \u2013 Won the top prize on April 10, 2001; however, because of the jackpot having been set to increase by $10,000 each episode, he won $2,180,000 \u2013 making him the biggest winner in television history at the time.<ref name=Jackpot>{{cite news|title=Double jackpot winner on US Millionaire|work=BBC News|date=April 11, 2001 |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1271553.stm|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n*Bernie Cullen \u2013 Won the top prize just five days after Olmstead's win on April 15, 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2001/04/16/improbably-millionaire-strikes-again/ |title=Improbably, ''Millionaire'' Strikes Again|work=[[New York Post]]|last=Kaplan|first=Don|date=April 16, 2001|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref>\n*Ed Toutant \u2013 Won on September 7, 2001. Originally appeared on January 31, 2001, when the jackpot was at $1,860,000 when he was ruled out after answering his $16,000 question wrong. However, it was determined that there was an error in the question, so he was invited back and won the jackpot as it was at the time.<ref>{{cite episode|series=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire |season=3|number=1|date=September 7, 2001|network=ABC}}</ref>\n*Kevin Smith \u2013 First syndicated millionaire, winning the top prize on February 18, 2003.<ref name=\"futon critic\u2014syndication\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news.aspx?id=20041027buenavista01|title='Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' Pulls Out All the Stops for November Sweeps|website=The Futon Critic|date=October 27, 2004|accessdate=August 21, 2018}}</ref>\n*Nancy Christy \u2013 Won the million on May 8, 2003. Christy is the only female top prize winner.<ref name=\"futon critic\u2014syndication\"/> \n*Sam Murray \u2013 Answered his question correctly during the Million Dollar Tournament of Ten and remained the only contestant to answer his question correctly on November 11, 2009.<ref name=\"Murray millionaire\">{{cite web|url=https://www.thoughtco.com/millionaire-tournament-of-ten-results-1397071|title='Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' Tournament of Ten Results|last=Grosvenor|first=Carrie|publisher=ThoughtCo|accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personnel==\n===Hosts===\n[[File:Regis Philbin at the 2009 Tribeca Film Festival.jpg|thumb|200px|Regis Philbin, host of the original network version]]\nThe original network version of the U.S. ''Millionaire'' and the subsequent primetime specials were hosted by [[Regis Philbin]].<ref name=\"Primetime Millionaire Returns\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/209778-_Who_Wants_To_Be_a_Millionaire_Returning_To_ABC.php |title=Who Wants To Be a Millionaire? Returning To ABC|last=Weprin |first=Alex |magazine=[[Broadcasting & Cable]]|date=April 22, 2009|accessdate=April 18, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120420122750/http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/209778-_Who_Wants_To_Be_a_Millionaire_Returning_To_ABC.php|archivedate=April 20, 2012}}</ref> When the syndicated version was being developed, the production team felt that it was not feasible for Philbin to continue hosting, as the show recorded four episodes in a single day, and that the team was looking for qualities in a new host: it had to be somebody who would love the contestants and be willing to root for them.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\">{{Cite episode|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|series=Gameshow Hall of Fame|publisher=GSN|airdate=January 21, 2007}}</ref> [[Rosie O'Donnell]] was initially offered a hosting position on this new edition, but declined the opportunity almost immediately.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Entertainment/story?id=104337|title=Daytime 'Millionaire' Considered|date=June 8, 2001 |publisher=ABC News|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> Eventually [[Meredith Vieira]], who had previously competed in a celebrity charity event on the original network version, was named host of the new syndicated edition.<ref name=\"weekday millionaire\">{{Cite news|title=''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' Kicks Off Coast to Coast Bus Tour|date=July 23, 2002|publisher=BusinessWire|quote=The weekday version of ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire,'' featuring Meredith Vieira as host, premieres on Monday, September 16 in nationwide syndication.}}</ref>\n\nABC originally offered Vieira hosting duties on the syndicated ''Millionaire'' to sweeten one of her re-negotiations for the network's daytime talk show ''[[The View (American TV series)|The View]]'', which she was moderating at the time.<ref name=\"Vieira leaves Millionaire\"/> When the show was honored by [[Game Show Network|GSN]] on its ''Gameshow Hall of Fame'' special, Vieira herself further explained her motivation for hosting the syndicated version as follows:\n\n{{quote|I did the show because I fell in love with the show, and really, first and foremost, as a parent, [I feel that] there aren't that many shows on television that you can watch as a family. And when Michael Davies approached me and said, \"Would you be interested in hosting the syndicated version?\", I said, \"Just point me toward the contract! I am so there!\"<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>}}\n\nFrom 2007 to 2011, when Vieira was concurrently working as a co-host of ''[[Today (American TV program)|Today]]'', guest hosts appeared in the second half of each season of the syndicated version. Guest hosts who filled in for Vieira included Philbin,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/network-press-releases/regis-philbin-hosts-daytime-millionaire-november-30-december-4/34625/|title=Regis Philbin Hosts Daytime Millionaire November 30 \u2013 December 4|work=TV By the Numbers|publisher=Zap2it|last=Seidman|first=Robert|date=November 25, 2009|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> [[Al Roker]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://origin.firstcoastnews.com/news/article/77189/3/Al-Roker-Fills-in-on-Who-Wants-To-Be-a-Millionaire-1st-Contestant-from-Jacksonville|title=Al Roker Fills in on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'', 1st Contestant from Jacksonville|work=First Coast News|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|date=March 5, 2007|accessdate=July 29, 2014|archiveurl=https://archive.today/20140806041455/http://origin.firstcoastnews.com/news/article/77189/3/Al-Roker-Fills-in-on-Who-Wants-To-Be-a-Millionaire-1st-Contestant-from-Jacksonville|archivedate=August 6, 2014}}</ref> [[Tom Bergeron]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.southbendtribune.com/2007-05-18/news/26789449_1_science-teacher-math-teacher-answer|title=Who doesn't want to win a million?|work=South Bend Tribune|last=Mumford|first=Lou|date=May 18, 2007|accessdate=January 27, 2019}}</ref> [[Tim Vincent]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.akron.com/20070712/wsl6.asp|title=Resident Takes Turn in ''Millionaire'' Hot Seat|publisher=Akron.com|last=Folkerth|first=Kathleen|date=July 12, 2007|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Dave Price]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lauranachman.wordpress.com/2008/03/04/former-good-day-philadelphia-host-dave-price-subs-on-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire/|title=Former ''Good Day Philadelphia'' Host Dave Price Subs on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''|publisher=Philly TV and Radio|last=Nachman|first=Laura|date=March 4, 2008|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Billy Bush]],<ref name=GuestHosts>{{cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire/cast/|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire Cast|publisher=tv.com|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Leeza Gibbons]],<ref name=GuestHosts/> [[Cat Deeley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.celebsnow.co.uk/tv-news/cat-deeley-to-present-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-in-the-states-216841|title=Cat Deeley to present Who Wants To Be A Millionaire in the States|work=[[NOW (UK magazine)|NOW]]|last=Arnold|first=Holly|date=October 3, 2008|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Samantha Harris]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/tv/samantha-harris-to-host-millionaire-for-a-week/|title=Samantha Harris to Host ''Millionaire'' \u2013 For a Week|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=Time Inc.|last=Rizzo|first=Monica|date=May 8, 2009|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Shaun Robinson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wkow.com/story/10478124/monroe-native-to-appear-on-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire|title=Monroe Native to Appear on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|publisher=WKOW|date=June 4, 2009|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Steve Harvey]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nj.com/hudson/index.ssf/2010/04/jersey_city_man_wins_15000_on.html|title=Jersey City Man Wins $15,000 on ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''|work=nj.com|author=The Jersey Journal|date=April 14, 2010|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[John Henson (comedian)|John Henson]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abc.go.com/shows/wipeout/cast/john-henson|title=Wipeout: John Henson|publisher=ABC|accessdate=July 30, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606191721/http://abc.go.com/shows/wipeout/cast/john-henson|archivedate=June 6, 2014}}</ref> [[Sherri Shepherd]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annarbor.com/entertainment/ann-arbor-resident-appearing-on-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-this-week/|title=Ann Arbor Resident Appearing on ''Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' this Week|work=[[The Ann Arbor News]]|last=Needham|first=Bob|date=March 14, 2011|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref> [[Tim Gunn]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mylifetime.com/shows/project-runway/blogs/project-runway-blog/tim-gunn-guest-hosts-millionaire |title=Tim Gunn Takes over ''Millionaire'' |publisher=[[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime]] |last=Bergmann |first=Caitlin |date=April 11, 2011 |accessdate=July 30, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110424120009/http://www.mylifetime.com/shows/project-runway/blogs/project-runway-blog/tim-gunn-guest-hosts-millionaire |archivedate=April 24, 2011 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and [[D. L. Hughley]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.upout.com/dc/do/dl-hughley-tony-roberts-timmy-hall-and-hope-flood|title=DL Hughley, Tony Roberts, Timmy Hall and Hope Flood|publisher=UpOut|accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn January 10, 2013, Vieira announced that after eleven seasons with the syndicated ''Millionaire'', she would be leaving the show as part of an effort to focus on other projects in her career. She finalized taping of her last episodes with the show in November 2012.<ref name=\"Vieira leaves Millionaire\">{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Meredith Vieira Leaving Syndicated \"Who Wants to Be a Millionaire\" Series|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/01/meredith-vieira-leaving-syndicated-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-series/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=January 10, 2013|accessdate=January 11, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520122144/http://www.deadline.com/2013/01/meredith-vieira-leaving-syndicated-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-series/|archivedate=May 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Stelter|first=Brian|title=Vieira to leave \"Who Wants to Be a Millionaire\"|url=http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/01/11/vieira-to-leave-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire/|work=[[The New York Times]] Media Decoder|date=January 11, 2013|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> While Philbin briefly considered a return to the show,<ref>{{cite web|last=Shain|first=Michael|title=Regis considering return to ''Who Wants to be a Millionaire''|url=https://nypost.com/2013/01/11/regis-considering-return-to-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire/|work=[[New York Post]]|date=January 11, 2013|accessdate=October 21, 2017}}</ref> [[Cedric the Entertainer]] was introduced as her successor when season twelve premiered on September 2, 2013.<ref name=\"cedric\">{{cite web|title=Cedric the Entertainer Will Host \"Who Wants to Be a Millionaire\", Replace Meredith Vieira|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/03/20/cedric-the-entertainer-millionaire-host_n_2916052.html?ncid=edlinkusaolp00000009|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=March 20, 2013|accessdate=September 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Cedric The Entertainer To Succeed Meredith Vieira As Host Of Syndicated ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire''|url=http://www.deadline.com/2013/02/cedric-the-entertainer-to-succeed-meredith-vieira-as-host-of-syndicated-%E2%80%98who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire%E2%80%99-series/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=February 7, 2013|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140102041339/http://www.deadline.com/2013/02/cedric-the-entertainer-to-succeed-meredith-vieira-as-host-of-syndicated-%E2%80%98who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire%E2%80%99-series/|archivedate=January 2, 2014|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> On April 30, 2014, ''[[Deadline Hollywood|Deadline]]'' announced that Cedric had decided to leave the show in order to lighten his workload,<ref name=\"CedricGoesPoof\">{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title='Who Wants To Be Millionaire' Host Cedric The Entertainer To Depart|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/who-wants-to-be-millionaire-host-cedric-the-entertainer-to-depart/#more-722117|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=April 30, 2014|accessdate=August 6, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140520155645/http://www.deadline.com/2014/04/who-wants-to-be-millionaire-host-cedric-the-entertainer-to-depart/|archivedate=May 20, 2014}}</ref> resulting in him being succeeded by [[Terry Crews]] for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"broadwayworld\">{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Terry Crews Named New Host of ''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire''|url=http://www.deadline.com/2014/05/terry-crews-named-new-host-of-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=May 7, 2014|accessdate=June 4, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606232844/http://www.deadline.com/2014/05/terry-crews-named-new-host-of-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire/|archivedate=June 6, 2014}}</ref> Crews was succeeded by [[Chris Harrison]], host of ''[[The Bachelor (American TV series)|The Bachelor]]'' and its spin-offs, when season 14 premiered on September 14, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|last=Andreeva|first=Nellie|title=Chris Harrison Named New Host Of 'Who Wants To Be A Millionaire', Replacing Terry Crews|url=https://deadline.com/2015/04/chris-harrison-host-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-terry-crews-replacement-1201409253/|work=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=2015-04-13}}</ref>\n\nOn January 8, 2020, a twentieth anniversary revival of the show was announced. Late night talk show host [[Jimmy Kimmel]] will host.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|last=Schneider|first=Michael|title=Jimmy Kimmel Hosts 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' 20th Anniversary Revival for ABC|url=https://variety.com/2020/tv/news/jimmy-kimmel-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-abc-20th-anniversary-1203460383/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=2020-01-08|access-date=2020-01-08|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Production staff===\nThe original [[executive producer]]s of the U.S. ''Millionaire'' were British television producers [[Michael Davies (television producer)|Michael Davies]] and Paul Smith,<ref name=\"Production credits\">End credits lists of appropriate U.S. ''Millionaire'' episodes.</ref> the latter of whom undertook the responsibility of licensing ''Millionaire'' to American airwaves as part of his effort to transform the UK program into a global franchise.<ref name=\"Walmsley\">{{Cite web|title=Millionaire|url=http://www.andywalmsley.com/millionaire.php|publisher=Andy Walmsley, Production Designer|accessdate=September 24, 2013}}</ref> Smith served until 2007 and Davies until 2010; additionally, Leigh Hampton (previously co-executive producer in the later days of the network version and in the syndicated version's first two seasons) served as an executive producer from 2004 to 2010. Rich Sirop, who was previously a supervising producer, became the executive producer in 2010 and held that position until 2014, when he left ''Millionaire'' to hold the same position with [[The Meredith Vieira Show|Vieira's newly launched syndicated talk show]],<ref>{{cite episode|series=[[The Meredith Vieira Show]]|season=1|number=1|date=September 8, 2014|network=Syndication}}</ref> and was replaced by James Rowley. Vincent Rubino, who had previously been the syndicated ''Millionaire''{{'}}s supervising producer for its first two seasons,<ref name=\"Production credits\"/> served as that version's co-executive producer for the 2004\u201305 season,<ref name=\"Switch\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/news/2004/08/24/switch-the-question-added-as-new-lifeline-on-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire--16778/20040824buenavista01/|title='Switch the Question' Added as New Lifeline on 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'|date=August 24, 2004|accessdate=December 16, 2012}}</ref> after which he was succeeded by Vieira herself, who continued to hold the title until her departure in 2013 (sharing her position with Sirop for the 2009\u201310 season).<ref name=\"Production credits\"/>\n\nProducers of the network version included Hampton, Rubino, Leslie Fuller, Nikki Webber, and Terrence McDonnell. For its first two seasons the syndicated version had Deirdre Cossman for its managing producer, then Dennis F. McMahon became producer for the next two seasons (joined by Dominique Bruballa as his line producer), after which Jennifer Weeks produced the next four seasons of syndicated ''Millionaire'' shows, initially accompanied by Amanda Zucker as her line producer, but later joined for the 2008\u201309 season by Tommy Cody (who became sole producer in the 2009\u201310 season). The first 65 shuffle format episodes were produced by McPaul Smith, and from 2011 onward, the title of producer was held by Bryan Lasseter. The network version had Ann Miller and Tiffany Trigg for its supervising producers; they were joined by Wendy Roth in the first two seasons, and by Michael Binkow in the third and final season. After Rubino's promotion to co-executive producer, the syndicated version's later supervising producers included Sirop (2004\u201309), Geena Gintzig (2009\u201310), Brent Burnette (2010\u201312), Geoff Rosen (2012\u201314), and Liz Harris (2014\u201316), who was the show's last co-executive producer.<ref name=\"Production credits\"/> \n\nThe original network version of ''Millionaire'' was directed by Mark Gentile, who later served as the syndicated version's consulting producer for its first two seasons; he went on to serve as the director of ''[[Duel (American game show)|Duel]]'' (which ran on ABC from December 2007 to July 2008) and ''[[Million Dollar Password]]'' (which aired on CBS from June 2008 to June 2009). The syndicated version was directed by Matthew Cohen from 2002 to 2010, by Rob George from 2010 to 2013, and by Brian McAloon in the 2013\u201314 season. Former ''[[The Price Is Right (American game show)|The Price Is Right]]'' director Rich DiPirro (who later directed ''[[Mental Samurai]]'') became ''Millionaire''{{'}}s director in 2014, and was later replaced by Ron de Moraes after the 2016\u201317 season, who remained as director until the show's cancellation.<ref name=\"Production credits\"/>\n\n==Production==\nThe U.S. version of ''Millionaire'' was a co-production of [[2waytraffic]], a division of [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]], and [[Valleycrest Productions]], a division of [[The Walt Disney Company]]. 2waytraffic purchased ''Millionaire''{{'}}s original production company [[Celador]] in 2008,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/sony-buys-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-parent|title=Sony buys Who Wants To Be a Millionaire? parent|date=March 13, 2008|publisher=mcvuk.com|accessdate=July 16, 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140725115910/http://www.mcvuk.com/news/read/sony-buys-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-parent|archivedate=July 25, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toynews-online.biz/news/read/new-owners-take-on-celador-international-and-millionaire-brand/039482|title=New owners take on Celador International and Millionaire brand|last=Loveday|first=Samantha|publisher=toynews-online.biz|date=December 1, 2006|accessdate=July 16, 2014}}</ref> while Valleycrest remained throughout the show's history,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.powerprofiles.com/profile/00005164543824/VALLEYCREST+PRODUCTIONS+LTD.-BURBANK-CA |title=Valleycrest Productions LTD |publisher=PowerProfiles |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131224114343/http://www.powerprofiles.com/profile/00005164543824/VALLEYCREST%2BPRODUCTIONS%2BLTD.-BURBANK-CA |archivedate=December 24, 2013 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> and holds the copyright on all U.S. ''Millionaire'' episodes to date. The show was distributed by Valleycrest's corporate sibling [[Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television|Disney-ABC Home Entertainment & Television Distribution]] (previously known as Buena Vista Television).\n\nThe U.S. ''Millionaire'' was taped at [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]'s ''Television Center East'' studio on the [[Upper West Side]] of [[Manhattan]] in New York from 1999 to 2012. Tapings were moved to [[NEP Broadcasting]]'s Metropolis Studios in [[East Harlem]] in 2013,<ref name=Reaves/> and production moved to studios located in [[Stamford, Connecticut]] the following year.<ref name=ctp>{{cite news|last1=Just|first1=Olivia|title=Disney moves filming of 'Millionaire' to Stamford|url=http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Disney-moves-filming-of-Millionaire-to-Stamford-5597151.php|accessdate=May 22, 2015|work=CT Post|publisher=[[Hearst Corporation|Hearst Media Services Connecticut, LLC]]|date=July 3, 2014}}</ref> For the final three seasons, production relocated to [[Bally's Las Vegas|Bally's Hotel and Casino]] in [[Las Vegas, Nevada]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/tv/news/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-to-las-vegas-1201779755/|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Relocates to Las Vegas|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|last=Holloway|first=Daniel|date=May 20, 2016|accessdate=November 5, 2016}}</ref> Episodes of the syndicated version were produced from June to December.<ref name=\"millionairetv\"/> The show originally taped four episodes in a single day,<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> but that number later changed to five.\n\n===Origins===\nWhen the U.S. version of ''Millionaire'' was first conceived in 1998, Michael Davies was a young television producer who was serving as the head of ABC's little-noticed reality programming division (at a time when [[reality television]] had not yet become a phenomenon in America).<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> At that time, ABC was lingering in third place in the ratings indexes among U.S. broadcast networks, and was on the verge of losing its status as one of the [[Big Three television networks|\"Big Three\" networks]].<ref name=\"Furman & Furman\">{{cite book|title=So You'd Like to Win a Million: Facts, Trivia, and Inside Hints on Game Show Success|last1=Furman|first1=Elina|last2=Furman|first2=Leah|year=2000|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=9780312976354|url=https://archive.org/details/soyoudliketowinm0000furm}}</ref> Meanwhile, the popularity of game shows was at an all-time low, and with the exception of ''[[The Price Is Right (American game show)|The Price Is Right]]'', the genre was absent from networks' daytime lineups at that point. Having earlier created ''[[Debt (game show)|Debt]]'' for [[Lifetime (TV network)|Lifetime Television]] and participated with Al Burton and Donnie Brainard in the creation of ''[[Win Ben Stein's Money]]'' for [[Comedy Central]],<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> Davies decided to create a primetime game show that would save the network from collapse and revive interest in game shows.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n\nDavies originally considered reviving [[CBS]]'s long-lost quiz show ''[[The $64,000 Question]]'', with a new home on ABC.<ref>{{cite book|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: The Official Book from the Hit TV Show|last1=Davies|first1=Michael|year=2000|publisher=Hyperion Books|isbn=9780786885770|page=[https://archive.org/details/whowantstobemill00fish/page/14 14]|url=https://archive.org/details/whowantstobemill00fish/page/14}}</ref> However, this effort's development was limited as when the producer heard that the British ''Millionaire'' was about to make its debut, he got his friends and family members in the UK to record the show, and subsequently ended up receiving about eight [[FedEx]] packages from different family members, each containing a copy of ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s first episode. Davies was so captivated by everything that he had seen and heard, from host [[Chris Tarrant]]'s intimate involvement with the contestant to the show's lighting system and music tracks, that he chose to abandon his work on the ''$64,000 Question'' revival in favor of introducing ''Millionaire'' to American airwaves, convinced that it would become extraordinarily popular.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n\nWhen Davies presented his ideas for the U.S. ''Millionaire'' to ABC, the network's executives initially rejected them, so he resigned his position there and became an independent producer.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> Determined to bring his idea for the show to fruition, Davies decided that he was betting his whole career on ''Millionaire''{{'}}s production, and the first move that he made was planning to attach a celebrity host to the show. Along with Philbin, a number of other popular television personalities were considered for hosting positions on the U.S. ''Millionaire'' during its development, including [[Peter Jennings]],<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> [[Bob Costas]], [[Phil Donahue]], and [[Montel Williams]],<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=msDfDRx6OK4C&pg=PA147&lpg=PA147&dq=Bob+Costas,+Phil+Donahue,+and+Montel+Williams,&source=bl&ots=vhUiVfMMVj&sig=ZbvvC89-UDTTvoO46tsqQS3lq98&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwje_J3qgffYAhWNyVMKHQl9AIEQ6AEIPDAH#v=onepage&q=Bob%20Costas%2C%20Phil%20Donahue%2C%20and%20Montel%20Williams%2C&f=false|title=Regis!: The Unauthorized Biography|last=Tracy|first=Kathleen|publisher=ECW Press|page=147|isbn=9781550224399|year=2000}}</ref> but among those considered, it was Philbin who wanted the job the most, and when he saw an episode of the British ''Millionaire'' and was blown away by his content, Davies and his team ultimately settled on having him host the American show.<ref name=\"Furman & Furman\"/> When Davies approached ABC again after having hired Philbin, the network finally agreed to accept the U.S. ''Millionaire''.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> With production now ready to begin, the team had only five months to finish developing the show and get it launched, with Davies demanding perfection in every element of ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s production.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n\n===Audition process===\nWith few exceptions, any legal resident of the United States who was 18 years of age or older had the potential of becoming a contestant through ''Millionaire''{{'}}s audition process. Those ineligible included employees, immediate family or household members, and close acquaintances of SPE, Disney, or any of their respective affiliates or subsidiaries; television stations that broadcast the syndicated version; or any advertising agency or other firm or entity engaged in the production, administration, or judging of the show. Also ineligible were candidates for political office and individuals who had appeared on a different game show outside of cable that had been broadcast within the past year, was intended to be broadcast within the next year, or had played the main game on any of the U.S. versions of ''Millionaire'' itself.<ref name=\"millionairetv\"/>\n\nPotential contestants of the original primetime version had to compete in a telephone contest which had them dial a toll-free number and answer three questions by putting objects or events in order. Callers had ten seconds to enter the order on a keypad, with any incorrect answer ending the game/call. The 10,000 to 20,000 candidates who answered all three questions correctly were selected into a random drawing in which approximately 300 contestants competed for ten spots on the show using the same phone quiz method.{{refn|To qualify for 2004's ''Super Millionaire'' spin-off, potential contestants were required to answer five questions. Each person who successfully answered all five questions chose one tape date, and the contestants for that tape date were drawn from that pool.|group=note}} Accommodations for contestants outside the New York City area included round trip airfare (or other transportation) and hotel accommodations.\n\nThe syndicated version's potential contestants, depending on tryouts, were required to pass an electronically scored test<ref name=\"About.com\">{{cite web|url=http://gameshows.about.com/od/beacontestant/a/wwtbamauditions.htm |title=Be a Contestant on Who Wants to be a Millionaire |last=Grosvenor |first=Carrie |publisher=about.com |accessdate=August 13, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161113020940/http://gameshows.about.com/od/beacontestant/a/wwtbamauditions.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2016 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> comprising a set of thirty questions which had to be answered within a 10-minute time limit. Contestants who failed the test were eliminated, while those who passed were interviewed for an audition by the production staff,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://old.seattletimes.com/html/television/2003638513_tvgameshowaudition28.html|title=Who wants to be a game-show contestant?|first=Claudia|last=Perry|date=March 28, 2007|work=The Seattle Times|accessdate=July 16, 2010}}</ref> and those who impressed the staff the most were then notified by postal mail that they had been placed into a pool for possible selection as contestants. At the producers' discretion, contestants from said pool were selected to appear on actual episodes of the syndicated program; these contestants were given a phone call from staff and asked to confirm the information on their initial application form and verify that they met all eligibility requirements. Afterwards, they were given a date to travel to the show's taping facilities to participate in a scheduled episode of the show.<ref name=\"About.com\"/> Unlike its ABC counterpart, the syndicated version did not offer transportation or hotel accommodations to contestants at the production company's expense; that version's contestants were instead required to provide transportation and accommodations of their own.<ref name=\"millionairetv\"/>\n\nThe syndicated ''Millionaire'' also conducts open casting calls in various locations across the United States to search for potential contestants. These are held in late spring or early summer, with all dates and locations posted on the show's official website. The producers make no guarantee on how many applicants will be tested at each particular venue;<ref name=\"About.com\"/> however, the show will not test any more than 2,500 individuals per audition day.<ref name=\"millionairetv\"/>\n\nIn cases when the show features themed episodes with two people playing as a team, auditions for these episodes' contestants are announced on the show's website. Both members of the team must pass the written test and the audition interview successfully in order to be considered for selection. If only one member of the team passes, he or she is placed into the contestant pool alone and must continue the audition process as an individual in order to proceed.<ref name=\"About.com\"/>\n\n===Music===\nOriginally, the U.S. ''Millionaire'' carried over the musical score from the British version, composed by father-and-son duo [[Keith Strachan|Keith]] and [[Matthew Strachan]]. Unlike older game show musical scores, ''Millionaire''{{'}}s musical score was created to feature music playing almost throughout the entire show. The Strachans' main ''Millionaire'' [[theme song]] took some inspiration from the \"Mars\" movement of [[Gustav Holst]]'s ''[[The Planets]]'',<ref name=\"Million Dollar Notes\">{{cite news|title=Million Pound Notes: Keith Strachan|last=Smurthwaite|first=Nick|newspaper=[[The Stage]]|date=March 21, 2005|url=http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6991|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110612081217/http://www.thestage.co.uk/features/feature.php/6991|archivedate=June 12, 2011}}</ref> and their question cues from the $2,000 to the $32,000/$25,000 level, and then from the $64,000/$50,000 to $500,000 level, took the pitch up a semitone for each subsequent question, in order to increase tension as the contestant progressed through the game.<ref name=\"Million Dollar Notes\"/> On GSN's ''Gameshow Hall of Fame'' special, the narrator described the Strachan tracks as \"mimicking the sound of a beating heart\", and stated that as the contestant worked their way up the money ladder, the music was \"perfectly in tune with their ever-increasing pulse\".<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n\nThe original ''Millionaire'' musical score holds the distinction of being the only game show soundtrack to be acknowledged by the [[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]], as the Strachans were honored with numerous ASCAP awards for their work, the earliest of them awarded in 2000.<ref name=\"Million Dollar Notes\"/> The original music cues were given minor rearrangements for the clock format in 2008; for example, the question cues were synced to the \"ticking\" sounds of the game clock. Even later, the Strachan score was removed from the U.S. version altogether for the introduction of the shuffle format in 2010, in favor of a new musical score with cues written by Jeff Lippencott and Mark T. Williams, co-founders of the Los Angeles-based company [[Ah2 Music]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Ah2 Music Marks 10th Anniversary|url=http://www.trailermusicvibe.com/ah2-music-marks-10th-anniversary/|publisher=TrailerMusicVibe|date=August 21, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Set===\nThe U.S. ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s basic set was a direct adaptation of the British version's set design, which was conceived by [[Andy Walmsley]]. Paul Smith's original licensing agreement for the U.S. ''Millionaire'' required that the show's set design, along with all other elements of the show's on-air presentation (musical score, lighting system, host's wardrobe, etc.), adhere faithfully to the way in which they were presented in the British version; this same licensing agreement applied to all other international versions of the show, making Walmsley's ''Millionaire'' set design the most reproduced scenic design in television history.<ref name=\"Walmsley\"/> The original version of the U.S. ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s set cost $200,000 to construct.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> The U.S. ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s [[Production designer|production design]] was handled at different times by David Weller, Jim Fenhagen and George Allison.<ref name=\"Production credits\"/>\n\nUnlike older game shows whose sets are or were designed to make the contestant(s) feel at ease, ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s set was designed to make the contestant feel uncomfortable, so that the program feels more like a movie thriller than a typical quiz show.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> The floor is made of [[Plexiglas]]<ref name=\"Walmsley\"/> beneath which lies a huge dish covered in mirror paper.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> Before the shuffle format was implemented in 2010, the main game had the contestant and host sit in chairs in the center of the stage, known as \"Hot Seats\"; these measured {{convert|3|ft|m}} high, were modeled after chairs typically found in [[hair salon]]s,<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> and each seat featured a computer monitor directly facing it to display questions and other pertinent information. Shortly after the shuffle format was introduced to ''Millionaire'', Vieira stated in an interview with her ''Millionaire'' predecessor on [[Live with Kelly and Michael|his morning talk show]] that the Hot Seat was removed because it was decided that the seat, which was originally intended to make the contestant feel nervous, actually ended up having contestants feel so comfortable in it that it did not service the production team any longer.<ref name=\"Regis and Kelly\">{{Cite episode|title=Season 23, Episode 8|series=Live! with Regis and Kelly|airdate=September 15, 2010|network=Syndicated|credits=Disney-ABC Domestic Television}}</ref>\n\nThe lighting system was programmed to darken the set as the contestant progressed further into the game. There were also spotlights situated at the bottom of the set area that zoomed down on the contestant when they answered a major question; to increase the visibility of the light beams emitted by such spotlights, oil was vaporized, creating a haze effect. [[Media scholar]] [[Robert Thompson (media scholar)|Dr. Robert Thompson]], a professor at [[Syracuse University]], stated that the show's lighting system made the contestant feel as though they were outside of prison when an escape was in progress.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n\nWhen the shuffle format was introduced, the Hot Seats and corresponding monitors were replaced with a single podium, so that the contestant and host stood throughout the game and were also able to walk around the stage.<ref name=\"Regis and Kelly\"/> Also, two video screens were installed\u2013one that displayed the current question in play, and another that displayed the contestant's cumulative total and progress during the game. In September 2012, the redesigned set was improved with a modernized look and feel, in order to take into account the show's transition to [[High-definition television|high-definition broadcasting]], which had just come about the previous year. The two video screens were replaced with two larger ones, having twice as many projectors as the previous screens had; the previous contestant podium was replaced with a new one; and [[light-emitting diode]] (LED) technology was integrated into the lighting system to give the lights more vivid colors and the set and gameplay experience a more intimate feel.<ref name=\"New set\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/anderson-live-wendy-williams-rachael-369024|title=''Anderson Live'', ''Wendy Williams'', ''Rachael Ray'' Among Syndicated Shows Getting Set Makeovers (Photos)|first=Kimberly|last=Nordyke|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=September 10, 2012|accessdate=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Broadcast history==\n===ABC===\nThe U.S. version of ''Millionaire'' was launched by ABC as a half-hour primetime program on August 16, 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/broadcast/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-returns-for-ten-year-anniversary/24432/|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Returns for its Ten Year Anniversary|work=[[TV By the Numbers]]|publisher=Zap2it|last=Seidman|first=Robert|date=August 9, 2009|accessdate=August 6, 2014}}</ref> When it premiered, it became the first U.S. network game show to offer a million-dollar top prize to contestants.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> After airing thirteen episodes and reaching an audience of 15 million viewers by the end of the show's first week on the air, the program expanded to an hour-long format when it returned in November.<ref name=\"Far from\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/08/09/arts/television/09cart.html?pagewanted=all|title=''Millionaire'' Far From Its Final Answer|last=Carter|first=Bill|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 9, 2009|accessdate=January 20, 2018}}</ref> The series, of which episodes were originally shown only a day after their initial taping, was promoted to regular status on January 18, 2000<ref>{{citation|title=Disney Factbook 2000 \u2013 Year in Review|author=Walt Disney Company|date=February 5, 2001|page=7}}</ref> and, at the height of its popularity, was airing on ABC five nights a week.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/05/abc-hopes-who-wants-to-be_n_251566.html |title=\"ABC Hopes \"Who Wants To Be A Millionaire\" Lightning Can Strike Twice\" |last=Bauder |first=David |work=[[Huffington Post]] |date=August 4, 2009 |accessdate=August 18, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304132904/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2009/08/05/abc-hopes-who-wants-to-be_n_251566.html |archivedate=March 4, 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The show was so popular during its original primetime run that rival networks created or re-incarnated game shows of their own (e.g., ''[[Greed (game show)|Greed]]'', ''[[Twenty One (game show)#2000|Twenty One]]'', etc.), as well as importing various game shows of British and Australian origin to America (such as ''[[Winning Lines (American game show)|Winning Lines]]'', ''[[Weakest Link (American game show)|Weakest Link]]'', and ''[[It's Your Chance of a Lifetime]]'').\n\nThe nighttime version initially drew in up to 30 million viewers a day three times a week, an unheard-of number in modern network television. In the 1999\u20132000 season, it averaged No. 1 in the ratings against all other television shows,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fbibler.chez.com/tvstats/recent_data/1999-00.html|title=TV Ratings 1999\u20132000|publisher=fbibler.chez.com|accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref> with 28,848,000 viewers. In the next season (2000\u201301), three nights out of the five weekly episodes placed in the top 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fbibler.chez.com/tvstats/recent_data/2000-01.html|title=TV Ratings 2000\u20132001|publisher=fbibler.chez.com|accessdate=March 2, 2010}}</ref> However, the show's ratings began to fall during the 2000\u201301 season, so that at the start of the 2001\u201302 season, the ratings were only a fraction of what they had been one year before, and by season's end, the show was no longer even ranked among the top 20.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fbibler.chez.com/tvstats/recent_data/2001-02.html|title=TV Ratings 2001\u20132002|publisher=fbibler.chez.com|accessdate=March 11, 2013}}</ref> ABC's reliance on the show's popularity led the network to fall quickly from its former spot as the nation's most watched network.\n\nAs ABC's overexposure of the primetime ''Millionaire'' led the public to tire of the show, there was speculation that the show would not survive beyond the 2001\u201302 season. The staff planned on switching it to a format that would emphasize comedy more than the game and feature a host other than Philbin,<ref>{{Cite news|title=ABC's ''Millionaire'' May Not Survive Beyond the Current Season|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/11/29/business/abc-s-millionaire-may-not-survive-beyond-the-current-season.html|last=Carter|first=Bill|work=The New York Times|date=November 29, 2001|accessdate=August 7, 2014}}</ref> but in the end, the primetime show was canceled, with its final episode airing on June 27, 2002.<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\">{{cite web|url=http://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-returning/|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'': ABC Game Show Returning to primetime|date=April 22, 2009|publisher=TV Series Finale|accessdate=March 2, 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn May 8, 2003 (the same day that Nancy Christy became the second top-prize winner on the syndicated version), ABC broadcast footage from [[Charles Ingram]]'s run on the British version of ''Millionaire'' as a special episode of ''[[Primetime (American TV program)|Primetime]]''; the documentary was originally broadcast in the United Kingdom on April 21, 2003 as an episode of ''[[Tonight (1999 TV programme)|Tonight]]'' that was hosted by [[Martin Bashir]]. During that program, Ingram was interviewed by [[Diane Sawyer]].<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/2823407.stm Millionaire's route to top prize] BBC News, 7 April 2003</ref>\n\n===Syndication===\nIn 2001, ''Millionaire'' producers began work on a half-hour daily syndicated version of the show, with producer Buena Vista Television (BVT) serving as distributor. Despite the ratings struggles of the network edition, there was still enough interest in ''Millionaire'' as a series that enough stations signed on for a fall 2002 launch; the original idea for the syndicated series to serve as an accompaniment to the network series did not come to fruition, as intended, due to ABC's decision to cancel ''Millionaire''.<ref name=\"weekday millionaire\"/><ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\"/> \n\nOn September 16, 2002, nearly three months after the network ''Millionaire'' ended its run, the syndicated series premiered. Right away, it found itself having similar ratings issues. Some stations began to look for other options to place in the slots where they had initially plugged ''Millionaire''; this included several larger market stations, especially their largest market affiliate, and thus ''Millionaire'' was looking at a second cancellation notice in less than a year. As fate would have it, though, this turn of events happened to coincide with a significant one going on at two of BVT's corporate siblings.\n\nWhen BVT initially sold ''Millionaire'' into syndication, the largest market station to come on board was [[WCBS-TV]] in New York, the flagship of the [[CBS]] network. Looking to bolster its offerings in the two hours between the end of CBS' daytime schedule and its first evening newscast of the day, which had been an ongoing problem for the station for years, ''Millionaire'' was one of two major additions to WCBS' lineup for the 2002\u20132003 season. The station gave it the 4 pm weekday timeslot that had housed ''[[Weakest Link (American game show)|Weakest Link]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2001/06/20/arts/tv-notes-games-to-clash-on-syndication.html|title=TV Notes: Games to Clash on Syndication|work=The New York Times|last=Carter|first=Bill|date=June 20, 2001|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://adage.com/article/special-report-hoagtest01/dr-phil-millionaire-john-walsh-arrive-heat-factor-lacking/52202/|title='Dr. Phil,' 'Millionaire,' 'John Walsh' arrive, but heat factor is lacking|magazine=Advertising Age|last=Pendleton|first=Jennifer|date=May 13, 2002|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> a syndicated version of another network primetime quiz show (in this case, produced by NBC) that had launched in January 2002.\n\nThe timeslot, at the time, was a fairly competitive one. [[WABC-TV]] had been airing ''[[The Oprah Winfrey Show]]'', which had consistently been the most popular daytime talk show, there since September 1986. [[WNBC]] at the time carried ''[[Judge Judy]]'', which was the second-highest rated program in daytime syndication behind ''Oprah''. ''Millionaire'' was unable to cut into the audience for either program, despite having the other major WCBS acquisition, the talk show ''[[Dr. Phil (talk show)|Dr. Phil]]'', as its lead in. WCBS again decided to switch its lineup.\n\nIn April 2003, with the season in its final weeks, WCBS announced its addition of ''[[The People's Court]]'' to its lineup for fall 2003 after the revived series had aired since its 1997 debut on WNBC.<ref name=\"Millionaire Poorer\"/> WCBS announced that ''The People's Court'' would be airing at 4:00 pm once it joined the station's lineup, which meant that ''Millionaire'' would be forced out of the timeslot after one year. BVT tried to negotiate with WCBS for another timeslot but the station had other obligations and thus could not accommodate them. There was not much in the way of open time slots on any of the other New York stations either, as they had other obligations in daytime and nighttime fringe slots, and BVT was in a position that could have seen ''Millionaire'' be reduced to airing in a post-midnight period or another non-traditional time that syndicators try to avoid.<ref name=\"Millionaire Poorer\">{{Cite news|url=http://business.highbeam.com/2012/article-1G1-95355049/millionaire-poorer-ny-game-loses-wcbs-plum-4-pm-slot|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140808042435/http://business.highbeam.com/2012/article-1G1-95355049/millionaire-poorer-ny-game-loses-wcbs-plum-4-pm-slot|url-status=dead|archive-date=August 8, 2014|title=''Millionaire'' poorer in N.Y.|url-access=subscription |work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Highbeam Business|date=December 2, 2002|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Millionaire Poorer\"/> \n\nMeanwhile, ABC was about to shake up its daytime schedule in a move made shortly after ''Millionaire'' concluded its season. The network had long programmed a thirty-minute serial at 12:30 pm, and since 1997 that time slot had belonged to ''[[Port Charles]]''. In July 2003, however, the network decided that it would be discontinuing the program after its contract to air it expired in October and, once that happened, the timeslot ''Port Charles'' had occupied would be given back to the affiliates to program as they wished. BVT decided to go to its parent company's flagship station and offered ''Millionaire'' to WABC as the replacement for ''Port Charles'', and the two sides agreed. Beginning in September 2003, ''Millionaire'' joined WABC's lineup and remained part of the station's lineup for the rest of its run.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/brief_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1967240|title=''Millionaire'' nabs key slots in syndication|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=September 2, 2003|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20030907080505/http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr/television/brief_display.jsp?vnu_content_id=1967240|archivedate=September 7, 2003}}</ref> ABC was impressed enough with the ratings improvement that the network, with one or two exceptions ([[WLS-TV]] in Chicago and [[KABC-TV]] in Los Angeles, though the latter would eventually add the series) picked up ''Millionaire'' for the other stations it owned.\n\nFollowing the 2014\u201315 season, ''Millionaire'' nearly was cancelled after a disagreement with BVT's successor, Disney-ABC Domestic Television, and [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]], the owner of the  format rights through its subsidiary [[2waytraffic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://millionairetv.dadt.com/local-listings/|title=Local Listings|publisher=Millionaire TV|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> According to e-mails released in the [[Sony Pictures Entertainment hack]], ''Millionaire'''s declining ratings prompted DADT to demand a dramatically reduced licensing fee for renewal, which SPE was hesitant to accept. The two sides eventually agreed on terms for renewal, which included a return to the original question format (but with fourteen questions) and cuts to the production budget, which resulted in the series leaving New York for [[Stamford, Connecticut]] (although this had been done in 2014) and later moving to [[Las Vegas]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Anotado|first=Cory|url=http://www.buzzerblog.com/2015/06/29/millionaire-re-introduces-ladder-format-for-2015-season/|title=Millionaire re-introduces ladder format for 2015 season|work=Buzzerblog|date=June 29, 2015|accessdate=June 29, 2015}}</ref> Had the show not been renewed, SPE was going to place the show on extended hiatus for three years, after which it would reclaim full rights to the show and be free to shop the revived show to another network or syndicator. DADT, meanwhile, would keep the rights to the format changes made in the late 2000s and early 2010s.<ref name=\"what millionaire needed\">{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzerblog.com/2015/04/17/what-millionaire-needed-to-stay-on-the-air/|first=Cory|last=Anotado|title=What Millionaire Needed to Stay On The Air|work=Buzzerblog|date=April 17, 2015|accessdate=April 28, 2015}}</ref> \n\nDespite its renewal, many of the stations airing ''Millionaire'', especially the ABC-owned stations, added the talk show ''[[FABLife]]'' for 2015. When ''FABlife'' failed to gain an audience and was cancelled at midseason, ''Millionaire'' was able to return to many of its former airing tines for 2016; beginning that year, ''Millionaire'' and the viral video show ''[[RightThisMinute]]'' began being sold as a package to ABC stations. \n\nOn January 17, 2017, it was announced that ''Millionaire'' has been renewed through 2018.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lincoln|first1=Ross|title=''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' & ''RightThisMinute'' Renewed For Syndication On ABC Stations Through 2018|url=http://deadline.com/2017/01/millionaire-rightthisminute-renewed-through-2018-on-abc-channels-1201884820/|website=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=PMC|date=January 17, 2017|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref> Millionaire was subsequently renewed through the 2018\u201319 season on January 17, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/live-feed/abc-renews-who-wants-be-a-millionaire-17th-season-1075368|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Renewed for 17th Season on ABC Stations|last=Sandberg|first=Bryn Elise|work=The Hollywood Reporter|date=January 17, 2018|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAs the seventeenth season progressed, the future of ''Millionaire'' became uncertain. Its strongest group of stations, the ABC-owned stations, had announced that they would be picking up a new [[Tamron Hall (talk show)|talk show]] hosted by former [[NBC News]] anchor and correspondent [[Tamron Hall]] for Fall 2019, making no announcement about the future of ''Millionaire'' with it; thus, it was speculated that the series would likely be facing its end. On May 17, 2019, the cancellation announcement came down, with ''Millionaire'' airing its final first-run episode on May 31, 2019.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Calvario |first1=Liz |title='Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' Canceled After Nearly 20 Years |url=https://www.etonline.com/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-canceled-after-nearly-20-years-125487 |website=ETOnline.com |publisher=CBS Studios, Inc. |accessdate=18 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===GSN===\n[[Game Show Network]] (GSN) acquired the rerun rights to the U.S. ''Millionaire'' in August 2003.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://business.highbeam.com/2012/article-1G1-108548491/gsn-wins-millionaire-rerun-rights|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714145109/http://business.highbeam.com/2012/article-1G1-108548491/gsn-wins-millionaire-rerun-rights|url-status=dead|archive-date=July 14, 2014|title=GSN Wins ''Millionaire'' Rerun Rights|last=Brennan|first=Steve|work=The Hollywood Reporter|publisher=Prometheus Global Media|date=September 23, 2003|accessdate=July 13, 2014}}</ref> The network initially aired only episodes from the three seasons of the original prime-time run; however, additional episodes were later added. These included the ''Super Millionaire'' spin-off,<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/gsn-renews-and-expands-its-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-inventory-and-acquires-super-millionaire-series-54331597.html|title=GSN Renews and Expands Its 'Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' Inventory and Acquires 'Super Millionaire' Series|publisher=PR Newswire|date=April 18, 2005|accessdate=June 7, 2014}}</ref> which aired on GSN from May 2005 to January 2007, and the first two seasons of the syndicated version, which began airing on November 10, 2008.<ref>{{cite press release|url=http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/meredith-vieira-hosted-%E2%80%9Cwho-wants-be-a-millionaire%E2%80%9D-episodes-make-cable-debut-beginni |title=Meredith Vieira-Hosted ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Episodes Make Cable Debut Beginning November 10, 2008 |publisher=GSN Corporate |date=November 10, 2008 |accessdate=June 7, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141010140133/http://corp.gsn.com/press/releases/meredith-vieira-hosted-%E2%80%9Cwho-wants-be-a-millionaire%E2%80%9D-episodes-make-cable-debut-beginni |archivedate=October 10, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> On December 4, 2017, GSN acquired the rerun rights to the Harrison episodes of ''Millionaire'' (seasons fourteen and fifteen), which began airing December 18, 2017.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwtv/article/GSN-Adds-WHO-WANTS-TO-BE-A-MILLIONAIRE-to-Daytime-Schedule-1218-20171204#|title=GSN Adds ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' to Daytime Schedule, 12/18|work=GSN Corporate|publisher=Broadway World|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://tvseriesfinale.com/tv-show/wants-millionaire-seasons-14-15-coming-gsn/|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'': Seasons 14 and 15 Coming to GSN|work=TV Series Finale|last=Avalos|first=Regina|date=December 6, 2017|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Special editions==\nVarious special editions and tournaments have been conducted which feature celebrities playing the game and donating winnings to charities of their choice. During celebrity editions on the original ABC version, contestants were allowed to receive help from their fellow contestants during the first ten questions. The most successful celebrity contestants throughout the show's run were [[Drew Carey]],<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\"/> [[Rosie O'Donnell]],<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\"/> [[Norm Macdonald]],<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\"/> and [[Chip Esten]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/chip-esten-on-nashville-finale-shows-future/|title=Chip Esten on ''Nashville'' Finale, Show's Future|publisher=CBS News|last=Moraski|first=Lauren|date=May 7, 2014|accessdate=July 20, 2014}}</ref> all of whom won $500,000 for their respective charities. The episode featuring O'Donnell's $500,000 win averaged 36.1 million viewers, the highest number for a single episode of the show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2000/05/05/2000-05-05_starstruck__millionaire__cel.html|title=Starstruck ''Millionaire'': Celebrity Specials Win Show its Best Ratings Ever|work=New York Daily News|last=Huff|first=Richard|date=May 5, 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090813142447/http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/entertainment/2000/05/05/2000-05-05_starstruck__millionaire__cel.html|archivedate=August 13, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThere have also been special weeks featuring two or three family members or couples competing as a team, a \"Champions Edition\" where former big winners returned and split their winnings with their favorite charities, a \"Zero Dollar Winner Edition\" featuring contestants who previously missed one of the first-tier questions and left with nothing, and a \"Tax-Free Edition\" in which [[H&R Block]] calculated the taxes of winnings to allow contestants to earn stated winnings after taxes, and various theme weeks featuring college students, teachers, brides-to-be, etc. as contestants.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.digitalspy.com/tv/ustv/news/a3710/season-premiere/|title=Season Premiere|work=[[Digital Spy]]|publisher=[[Hearst Magazines UK]]|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> Additionally, the syndicated version once featured an annual \"Walk In & Win Week\" with contestants who were randomly selected from the audience without having to take the audition test.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dadt.com/millionaire/special/americanpride/rules.html|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'': Walk in and Win|publisher=dadt.com|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nSpecial weeks have also included shows featuring questions concerning specific topics, such as professional football, celebrity gossip, movies, and pop culture. During a week of episodes in November 2007, to celebrate the 1,000th episode of the syndicated ''Millionaire'', all contestants that week started with $1,000 so that they could not leave empty-handed, and only had to answer ten questions to win $1,000,000. During that week, twenty home viewers per day also won $1,000 each.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwired.com/press-release/Who-Wants-To-Be-A-Millionaire-Host-Meredith-Vieira-Celebrate-1000-Episodes-Giving-784227.htm|title=''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'', and Host Meredith Vieira, Celebrate 1,000 Episodes by Giving $100,000 Away to Home Viewers!|publisher=[[Marketwired]]|date=October 23, 2007|accessdate=August 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===''Who Wants to Be a Super Millionaire''===\nIn 2004, Philbin returned to host 12 episodes of a spin-off program titled ''Who Wants to Be a Super Millionaire'' in which contestants could potentially win '''$10,000,000'''.<ref name=SuperMillionaire>{{cite web|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2004-02-23-millionaire_x.htm |title=''Millionaire'' could be ABC's Interim Answer|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|last=Levin|first=Gary|date=February 24, 2004|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> ABC aired five episodes of this spin-off during the week of February 22, 2004, and an additional seven episodes later that year in May. As usual, contestants had to answer a series of 15 multiple-choice questions of increasing difficulty, but the dollar values rose substantially. The questions for ''Super Millionaire'' were worth $1,000, $2,000, $3,000, $4,000, $5,000 (the first safe haven), $10,000, $20,000, $30,000, $50,000, $100,000 (the second safe haven), $500,000, $1,000,000, $2,500,000, $5,000,000, and '''$10,000,000'''.\n\nContestants were given the standard three lifelines in place at the time (50:50, Ask the Audience, and Phone-a-Friend) at the beginning of the game. However, after correctly answering the $100,000 question, the contestant earned two additional lifelines: Three Wise Men and Double Dip.<ref name=SuperMillionaire/> The Three Wise Men lifeline involved a panel of three experts, one of whom was always a former ''Millionaire'' contestant and at least one of whom was female. When this lifeline was used, the contestant and panel had 30 seconds to discuss the question and choices before the audio and video feeds were dropped. Double Dip gave a contestant two chances to answer a question. Once used, the contestant must answer the question without using any further lifelines; moreover, if the \"first final answer\" was incorrect, the contestant could ''not'' walk away. If the \"second final answer\" was also wrong, the contestant left with $100,000.\n\n===''10th Anniversary Celebration''===\nTo celebrate the tenth anniversary of ''Millionaire''{{'}}s U.S. debut, the show returned to ABC primetime for an eleven-night event hosted by Philbin, which aired from August 9 to 23, 2009.<ref name=\"accesshollywood.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.accesshollywood.com/articles/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-returns-with-a-hollywood-makeover-74474/|title=''Who Wants To Be A Millionaire'' Returns With A Hollywood Makeover|publisher=AccessHollywood.com|accessdate=April 2, 2017}}</ref> The [[Academy Awards|Academy Award]]-winning movie ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'' and the [[Late-2000s recession|2008 economic crisis]] helped boost interest of renewal of the game show.<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\"/>\n\nThe episodes featured game play based on the previous rule set of the syndicated version (including the rule changes implemented in season seven) but used the Fastest Finger round to select contestants. Various celebrities also made special guest appearances at the end of every episode; each guest played one question for a chance at $50,000 for a charity of their choice, being allowed to use any one of the four lifelines in place at the time (Phone-a-Friend, Ask the Audience, Double Dip, and Ask the Expert), but still earned a minimum of $25,000 for the charity if they answered the question incorrectly.<ref name=\"accesshollywood.com\"/>\n\nOn August 18, 2009, New York City resident [[Nik Bonaddio]] appeared on the program, winning $100,000 with the help of the audience and later, [[Gwen Ifill]] as his lifelines.<ref>{{cite episode|series=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: 10th Anniversary Celebration|network=ABC|date=August 18, 2009|number=6}}</ref> Bonaddio then used the proceeds to start the sports analytics firm [[numberFire]],<ref name=\"fastcompany.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1824128/numberfire-moneyball-fantasy-leagues|title=numberFire: ''Moneyball'' for Fantasy Football Leagues|publisher=FastCompany.com|accessdate=September 3, 2016}}</ref> which was sold in September 2015 to [[FanDuel]], a fantasy sports platform.\n{{WWTBAM question\n| float    = right\n| value    = $1,000,000 (15 of 15) \u2013 4:39 time limit\n| question = For ordering his favorite beverages on demand, LBJ had four buttons installed in the Oval Office labeled \"coffee\", \"tea\", \"Coke\" and what?\n| a        = Fresca\n| b        = V8\n| c        = Yoo-hoo\n| d        = A&W\n| astyle   = correct\n| bstyle   = \n| cstyle   = chosen\n| dstyle   = \n| caption  = Ken Basin's million-dollar question\n}}\nThe finale of the tenth anniversary special, which aired on August 23, 2009, featured Ken Basin, an entertainment lawyer from Los Angeles, California, who went on to become the first contestant to play a $1,000,000 question in the \"clock format\". With a time of 4:39 (45 seconds + 3:54 banked time), Basin was given a question involving President [[Lyndon B. Johnson|Lyndon Baines Johnson]]'s fondness for [[Fresca]]. Using his one remaining lifeline, Basin asked the audience, which supported his own hunch of [[Yoo-hoo]] rather than the correct answer. He decided to answer the question and lost $475,000, becoming the first contestant in the U.S. version to answer a $1,000,000 question incorrectly. After Basin finished his run, Vieira appeared on-camera and announced that all remaining Fastest Finger contestants would play with her on the first week of the syndicated version's eighth season.<ref>{{cite episode|series=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: 10th Anniversary Celebration|network=ABC|date=August 23, 2009|number=11}}</ref> After this, the million dollar question was not played again on a standard episode until September 25, 2013,<ref name=Reaves>{{cite web|url=http://fox43.com/2013/09/24/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-has-the-first-million-dollar-question-of-the-season/#axzz38xr1mzbC|title=''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' has the First Million Dollar Question of the Season!|publisher=Fox 43 Central Pennsylvania|date=September 24, 2013|accessdate=July 30, 2014}}</ref> when Josina Reaves became the second U.S. ''Millionaire'' contestant to incorrectly answer her $1,000,000 question, but only lost $75,000 as she used her Jump the Question lifelines on her $250,000 and $500,000 questions.<ref>{{cite episode|season=12|number=18|series=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|network =Syndicated|date=September 25, 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Million Dollar Tournament of Ten===\nAlthough the syndicated ''Millionaire'' had produced two millionaires in its first season, Nancy Christy's May 2003 win was still standing as the most recent when the program began its eighth season in fall of 2009. Deciding that six-plus years had been too long since someone had won the top prize, producers conducted a tournament to find a third million dollar winner.<ref>{{Cite episode|season=8|number=1|series=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|network=Syndicated|date=September 7, 2009}}</ref> For the first nine weeks of the 2009\u201310 season, each episode saw contestants attempt to qualify for what was referred to as the \"Tournament of Ten\". Contestants were seeded based on how much money they had won, with the biggest winner ranked first and the lowest ranked tenth. Ties were broken based on how much time a contestant had banked when they had walked away from the game.<ref name=\"Tournament\">{{cite web|url=http://gameshows.about.com/od/millionaireglossary/g/tournament_of_ten.htm |title='Who Wants to Be a Millionaire' Tournament of Ten |publisher=about.com |accessdate=July 16, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091113062329/http://gameshows.about.com/od/millionaireglossary/g/tournament_of_ten.htm |archivedate=November 13, 2009 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>\n\nThe tournament began on the episode aired November 9, 2009, and playing in order from the lowest to the highest seed, tournament contestants played one at a time at the end of that episode and the next nine. The rules were exactly the same as they were for a normal million dollar question under the clock format introduced the season before, except here, the contestants had no lifelines at their disposal. Each contestant received a base time of 45 seconds. For each question they had answered before walking away, the contestants received any unused seconds that were left when they gave their answers. The accumulated total of those unused seconds was then added to the base time to give the contestants their final question time limit.<ref name=\"Tournament\"/>\n\nEach contestant had the same decision facing them as before, which was whether to attempt to answer the question or walk away with their pre-tournament total intact. Attempting the question and answering incorrectly incurred the same penalty as in regular play, with a reduction of their pre-tournament winnings to $25,000. If the question was answered correctly, the player that did so became the tournament leader. If another player after him/her answered correctly, that player assumed the lead and the previous leader kept their pre-tournament winnings. The highest remaining seed to have attempted and correctly answered their question at the end of the tournament on November 20, 2009 would be declared the winner and become the syndicated series' third millionaire.<ref name=\"Tournament\"/>\n\nThe first contestant to attempt to answer the million dollar question was Sam Murray, the tournament's eighth-seeded qualifier. On November 11, Murray was asked approximately how many people had lived on Earth in its history and correctly guessed 100 billion. Murray was still atop the leaderboard entering the November 20 finale as he remained the only contestant to even attempt to answer his or her question. The only person who could defeat him was top seed and $250,000 winner Jehan Shamsid-Deen, who was asked a question regarding the [[Blorenge]], cited as \"a rare example of a word that rhymes with orange\". Shamsid-Deen considered taking the risk, believing (correctly) that the name belonged to a mountain in [[Wales]]. However, she decided that the potential of losing $225,000 did not justify the risk and elected to walk away from the question, giving Murray the win and the million dollar prize.<ref name=\"Murray millionaire\"/>\n\n==Reception==\nSince its introduction to the United States, GSN credited ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' with not only single-handedly reviving the game show genre, but also breaking new ground for it.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/> The series revolutionized the look and feel of game shows with its unique lighting system, dramatic music cues, and futuristic set. The show also became one of the highest-rated and most popular game shows in U.S. television history, and has been credited with paving the way for the rise of the primetime reality TV phenomenon to prominence throughout the 2000s.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/><ref name=\"Far from\"/>\n\nThe U.S. ''Millionaire'' also made catchphrases out of various lines used on the show. In particular, ''\"Is that your final answer?\"'', asked by ''Millionaire''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s hosts whenever a contestant's answer needs to be verified, was popularized by Philbin during his tenure as host,<ref name=\"tvseriesfinale.com\"/> and was also included on [[TV Land]]'s special \"100 Greatest TV Quotes and Catch Phrases\", which aired in 2006.<ref>The Star Ledger. December 11, 2006</ref> Meanwhile, during his tenure as host, Cedric signed off shows with a catchphrase of his own, ''\"Watch yo' wallet!\"''<ref name=\"CedricGoesPoof\"/>\n\nThe original primetime version of the U.S. ''Millionaire'' won two [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show|Daytime Emmy Awards for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]] in 2000 and 2001. Philbin was honored with a Daytime Emmy in the category of [[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show Host|Outstanding Game Show Host]] in 2001, while Vieira received one in 2005, and another in 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/Meredith_Vieira/1578769#awards |title=Meredith Vieira biography |publisher=www.hollywood.com |accessdate=March 11, 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321145229/http://www.hollywood.com/celebrity/Meredith_Vieira/1578769 |archivedate=March 21, 2008 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> ''[[TV Guide]]'' ranked the U.S. ''Millionaire'' #7 on its 2001 list of the 50 Greatest Game Shows of All Time,<ref>{{cite news|title=TV Guide Names the 50 Greatest Game Shows of All Time|work=[[TV Guide]]|date=February 2, 2001}}</ref> and later ranked it #6 on its 2013 \"60 Greatest Game Shows\" list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Eyes on the Prize|last=Fretts|first=Bruce|date=June 17, 2013|work=TV Guide|pages=14\u201315}}</ref> GSN ranked ''Millionaire'' #5 on its August 2006 list of the 50 Greatest Game Shows of All Time,<ref>{{cite episode|series=The 50 Greatest Game Shows of All Time|network=GSN|date=August 31, 2006}}</ref> and later honored the show in January 2007 on its only ''Gameshow Hall of Fame'' special.<ref name=\"Gameshow Hall of Fame\"/>\n\n==Other media==\n===Merchandise===\nIn 2000, [[Pressman Toy Corporation|Pressman]] released two board game adaptions of ''Millionaire''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/4077/who-wants-be-millionaire|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire|publisher=[[BoardGameGeek]]|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/166429/who-wants-be-millionaire-second-edition|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (Second Edition)|publisher=BoardGameGeek|accessdate=January 23, 2018}}</ref> as well as a junior edition recommended for younger players.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/10582/who-wants-be-millionaire-junior|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire Junior|publisher=BoardGameGeek|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> Several video games based on the varying gameplay formats of ''Millionaire'' have also been released throughout the course of the show's U.S. history.\n\nBetween 1999 and 2001, [[Jellyvision]] produced five video game adaptations based upon the original primetime series for [[personal computer]]s and [[Sony]]'s [[PlayStation]] console, all of them featuring Philbin's likeness and voice. The first of these adaptations was published by [[Disney Interactive Studios|Disney Interactive]], while the later four were published by [[Disney Interactive Studios#Buena Vista Games (2003\u201307)|Buena Vista Interactive]] which had just been spun off from DI when it reestablished itself in attempts to diversify its portfolio. Of the five games, three featured general trivia questions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-1999/pc-13563|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? [1999]|website=[[IGN]]|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-2nd-edition/pc-14900|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? Second Edition|website=IGN|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-3rd-edition/mac-855593|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? 3rd Edition|website=IGN|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref> one was sports-themed,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-sports-edition/pc-490819|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? Sports Edition|website=IGN|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref> and another was a \"Kids Edition\" featuring easier questions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/games/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-kids-collection/pc-732164|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? Kids Edition|website=IGN|accessdate=July 19, 2014}}</ref> In 2007, [[Imagination Games]] released a DVD version of the show, based on the 2004\u201308 format and coming complete with Vieira's likeness and voice,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boardgamegeek.com/boardgame/33974/who-wants-be-millionaire-dvd-game|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: DVD Game|publisher=BoardGameGeek|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> as well as a quiz book<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/millionaire-imagination-international/1113759882?ean=9781934524169|title=Millionaire: Quiz Book|publisher=[[Barnes & Noble]]|accessdate=July 22, 2014}}</ref> and a 2009 desktop calendar.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.deskcalendarpad.com/ecommerce/Desk+Calendars/millionaire_2009_desktop_calendar_0eec96ca |title=Millionaire 2009 Desktop Calendar |publisher=Desk Calendar Pad |accessdate=July 22, 2014 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722042832/http://www.deskcalendarpad.com/ecommerce/Desk%2BCalendars/millionaire_2009_desktop_calendar_0eec96ca |archivedate=July 22, 2014 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> Additionally, two ''Millionaire'' video games were released by [[Ludia]] in conjunction with [[Ubisoft]] in 2010 and 2011; the first of these was a game for [[Nintendo]]'s [[Wii]] console and [[Nintendo DS|DS]] handheld system based on the clock format,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2010/10/06/ubisoft-releases-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-videogame-for-wii-and-ds|title=Ubisoft Releases ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' Video Game for Wii and DS|website=IGN|date=October 6, 2010|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> while the second, for [[Microsoft]]'s [[Xbox 360]], was based on the shuffle format.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefaqs.com/xbox360/645007-who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-2012-edition|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? 2012 Edition|website=[[GameFAQs]]|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref>\n\nLudia made a Facebook game based on ''Millionaire'' available from 2011 to 2016. This game featured an altered version of the shuffle format, condensing the number of questions to twelve\u2014eight in round one and four in round two. Contestants competed against eight other ''Millionaire'' fans in round one, with the top three playing round two alone. There was no \"final answer\" rule; the contestant's responses were automatically locked in. Answering a question correctly earned a contestant the value of that question, multiplied by the number of people who responded incorrectly. Contestants were allowed to use two of their Facebook friends as Jump the Question lifelines in round one, and to use the Ask the Audience lifeline in round two to invite up to 50 such friends of theirs to answer a question for a portion of the prize money of the current question.<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire now on Facebook: Compete with others for virtual riches|url=https://www.aol.com/article/2011/04/07/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-now-on-facebook-compete-with-othe/19906686/|last=Shaul|first=Brandy|publisher=AOL|date=April 7, 2011|accessdate=April 2, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170404043122/https://www.aol.com/article/2011/04/07/who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire-now-on-facebook-compete-with-othe/19906686/|archivedate=April 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Album===\nWho Wants to Be a Millionaire: The Album (Celador Records), by [[Keith Strachan]], [[Matthew Strachan]], and various artists, was released August 1, 2000 and features songs based on the show.<ref>{{cite web |title=Keith Strachan & Matthew Strachan \u2013 Who Wants To Be A Millionaire (The Album) |url=https://www.discogs.com/Keith-Strachan-Matthew-Strachan-Who-Wants-To-Be-A-Millionaire-The-Album/release/3958022 |website=Discogs |accessdate=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Disney Parks attraction===\n{{Main|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire \u2013 Play It!}}\n[[File:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire - Play It! Sound Stage after 2004 closure.jpg|thumb|right|The building that housed the Californian version, shown here after its 2004 closure.]]\n''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire \u2013 Play It!]]'' was an attraction at the [[Disney's Hollywood Studios]] theme park (when it was known as ''Disney-MGM Studios'') at the [[Walt Disney World Resort]] in [[Orlando, Florida]] and at [[Disney California Adventure Park]] in [[Anaheim, California]]. Both the Florida and California ''Play It!'' attractions opened in 2001; the California version closed in 2004,<ref>{{cite book|last=Shaffer|first=Joshua C.|title=Discovering the Magic Kingdom: An Unofficial Disneyland Vacation Guide|publisher=Author House|year=2010|page=207|isbn=9781452063133}}</ref> and the Florida version closed in 2006 and was replaced by ''[[Toy Story Midway Mania!]]''\n\nThe format in the ''Play It!'' attraction was very similar to that of the television show that inspired it. When a show started, a Fastest Finger question was given, and the audience was asked to put the four answers in order; the person with the fastest time was the first contestant in the Hot Seat for that show. However, the main game had some differences: for example, contestants competed for points rather than dollars, the questions were set to time limits, and the Phone-a-Friend lifeline became ''Phone a Complete Stranger'' which connected the contestant to a Disney cast member outside the attraction's theater who would find a guest to help. After the contestant's game was over, they were awarded anything from a collectible pin, to clothing, to a ''Millionaire'' CD game, to a 3-night [[Disney Cruise Line|Disney Cruise]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Who Wants to Be a Winner? Passport Tips for ''Who Wants to Be a Millionaire \u2013 Play It!''|url=http://www.passporter.com/articles/millionairetips.asp|last=Marx|first=Jennifer and Dave|publisher=PassPorter.com|date=December 29, 2006}}</ref>\n{{Clear}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book|last1=Fisher|first1=David|last2=Davies|first2=Michael P.|authorlink2=Michael Davies (television producer)|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire: The Official Book from the Hit TV Show|year=2000|publisher=Cader Books|isbn=0-7868-8577-7|url=https://archive.org/details/whowantstobemill00fish}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://millionairetv.dadt.com/}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0211178|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (US \u2013 1999\u20132002)}}\n*{{tv.com show|who-wants-to-be-a-millionaire|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0321019|title=Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (US \u2013 current)}}\n*{{IMDb title|id=0412256|title=Who Wants to Be a Super Millionaire (US)}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{Succession box|before=[[Win Ben Stein's Money]]|title=[[Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show]]|years=2000\u20132001|after=[[Jeopardy!]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{Daytime Emmy Award Outstanding Game/Audience Participation Show}}\n{{TopUSTVShows}}\n{{ABCNetwork Shows (current and upcoming)}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Who Wants To Be A Millionaire (American Game Show)}}\n[[Category:1990s American game shows]]\n[[Category:1999 American television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2010s American game shows]]\n[[Category:2019 American television series endings]]\n[[Category:American Broadcasting Company original programming]]\n[[Category:American television series based on British television series]]\n[[Category:American television series revived after cancellation]]\n[[Category:Daytime Emmy Award for Outstanding Game Show winners]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:First-run syndicated television programs in the United States]]\n[[Category:Nielsen ratings winners]]\n[[Category:Quiz shows]]\n[[Category:Television series by Disney\u2013ABC Domestic Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by Sony Pictures Television]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]\n[[Category:Television programs adapted into video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the current season|Who Wants to Be a Millionaire (American game show, season 21)}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Who Wants to Be a Millionaire\n| image                    = File:WWTBAMUS2020Logo.png\n| genre                    = [[Game show]]\n| developer                = [[Michael Davies (television producer)|Michael Davies]]\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Mark Gentile <small>(1999\u20132002)</small>\n* Matthew Cohen <small>(2002\u201310)</small>\n* Rob George <small>(2010\u201313)</small>\n* Brian McAloon <small>(2013\u201314)</small>\n* Rich DiPirro <small>(2014\u201317)</small>\n* [[Ron de Moraes]] <small>(2017\u201319)</small>\n}}\n| presenter                = {{Plainlist|\n* ''ABC'':\n* [[Regis Philbin]]\